event.description: This poignant story full of music and dance plumbs a young girl’s diary. As she experiences typical growing pains, the tween learns the important role friendship plays in helping one cope with challenges. Ages 6 and up.

The museum marks the holiday with a festival of African and African-American arts. Your brood can take in dance, spoken word and musical performances or browse a marketplace of crafts and other visual arts. All ages.

The Seattle-based author of the vampire-themed Oliver Nocturne series reads from his latest installment, The Eternal Tomb. You can also see Emerson jam with his band, The Board of Education at 92YTribeca today while the group is still hanging around the East Coast. Ages 8 and up.
Kids and parents will enjoy themed songs, book readings, prizes and games, plus a full menu of tasty treats. Ages 1 to 8.

For this production, The Little Orchestra Society rewrote the entire script of the classic show, transforming Toyland from a fantastical Oz-like setting into an old-fashioned New York shop. When the eccentric storekeeper learns that his new partners are trying to take over, his apprentice steps in to save the day—with some help from the store’s merchandise. Ages 6 to 12.

The Frog & Peach Theatre Company presents two shows this holiday: 10:30am showtimes (program A) offer up “Cinderella”, based on the Brothers Grimm popular tale, while the 11:45am showtimes (program B) host “The Tenderbox” by Hans Christian Andersen. All ages.

event.identifier: Miracle on 34th Street at Macy's Puppet Theatre
event.description: After a trip to see the jolly guy in red at Macy's Santaland, view this 30-minute version of Miracle on 34th Street—with seven original songs, vocal work by Broadway pros such as Brian Stokes Mitchell and Victoria Clark, and artistry by Puppetworks. It runs continuously throughout the day. All ages.
event.sort_string: Miracle on 34th Street at Macy's Puppet Theatre

event.identifier: Anne and Bernard Spitzer Hall of Human Origins
event.description: The former Human Biology and Evolution Hall has evolved into an interactive space that retraces mankind’s progressively upright journey from ape to Homo sapiens. Two touch tables allow kids to feel the similarities and differences between various hominid bones, while wanna-be geneticists can “decode” DNA using fossil casts and molecular tools, while wanna-be geneticists can “decode” DNA with the help of fossil casts and molecular tools.
You won’t find any iPhone apps at this workshop, during which kids explore toys from a simpler era. They also decorate 19th-century-inspired playthings. Ages 4 and up.

event.identifier: An Irish Christmas: A Musical Solstice Celebration
event.description: Hosted by the Mick Moloney, this show features an eclectic mix of tunes ranging from solstice classics to familiar sing-along songs. Joining Moloney are star fiddler Athena Tergis, pianist Brendan Dolan, Irish dance champion Niall O'Leary, vocalist and fiddler Liz Hanley, accordionist Billy McComiskey and other guests. Ages 6 and up.

Parents and kids tour MoMA’s galleries in a fun and engaging way, sharing their ideas about the art and getting any questions answered by museum educators. A new theme is introduced each month, so you and your tot can get the scoop on everyone from Rauschenberg to Rothko. Ages 4 and up.

Take a trip into southern Spain’s Andalusia—the birthplace of Flamenco—at a performance by Flamenco Vivo/Carlota Santana. The 26-year-old group is a leading flamenco company in the U.S., so chances are good that your brood will get carried away by their moves. Stick around after the show for a Q&A session with the dancers. Ages 5 and up.
event.sort_string: Meet the Artist: Flamenco Vivo/Carlota Santana

event.description: The Bard’s classic tale of star-crossed lovers meets the energetic, passionate and masterful choreography of the New York City Ballet. Ages 8 and up.
This playspace offers plenty of options for busy parents: movie date nights, after-school programs, drop-off services, sleep-in Saturdays, party planning and more.
Hailing from Austin, Texas, this underground country-tinged blues band will perform original tunes from their first family-focused album, 2007’s Mommy Says No. All ages.
Singer Joshua Nelson and the Kosher Gospel Choir croon Jewish hymns and other favorites old and new. This popular sing-along has sold out in past years, so get your tickets early. Ages 8 and up.

Strawberry Fields is, of course, a Beatles tribute band. And it does the job pretty well, partly because the group includes former cast members from Beatlemania. In addition to Beatles classics, expect holiday jams at this family-friendly show. Doors open at 6pm. All ages.
Winard Harper, drummer for the New Jersey-based jazz radio station WBGO, headlines this interactive concert series. A Q&A session will follow the instrumental performance. Ages 6 to 16.

Forget the wishing well. In Japan, luck isn’t tossed into a fountain. Instead, the Japanese eat as many soybeans as their age to bring about good luck during Setsubun, the Spring Festival. Today’s family workshop teaches your lucky guy to chase off evil spirits with a homemade monster mask. All ages.

Together for almost a decade, this quintet plays original tunes, Beatles songs, and classics like “Hey, Good Lookin’ ” and “Somewhere over the Rainbow.” With six CDs under its belt, the group has proven that it knows how to please little ones. Offbeat instruments, including an accordion and a mandolin, supply extra flavor. Ages 3 to 8.

Don't leave teddy at home today! Kiddos can tote their favorite stuffed animals and dolls out to meet a costumed character of the Hotel proprietor's daughter, Sara Woodhull, who will regale tots with tales of yore. Tea and cookies will be served up along with the stories. Reservations recommended. Ages 3 to 6.

Celebrate Christmas Eve by belting out all of the classic carols alongside The Rob Susman Brass Quartet and the glow of the Washington Square Arch Christmas Tree. Complimentary songbooks, courtesy of the Washington Square Association, will be on hand just in case you forget the words to “Silent Night.” All ages.

After attending this performance, kids may view routine trips to the corner bodega differently. In the whimsical show, a child dozes off while sitting in mom’s shopping cart and dreams of a world in which vegetables are life-size (and, er, sentient). A piano soundtrack piece accompanies the quirky scenes, which impart humorous, easy-to-swallow lessons about brattiness and bravery. Ages 5 to 12.

The sky is the limit in this all day cosmic fare. Activities range from crafts to dance to a Universe-exploring film by the American Museum of Natural History. Leave room for storytelling, scavenger hunts, and visits to a star lab with the New York Hall of Science. Sounds like a lot of activities, but then again the universe is a big place. All ages.

event.identifier: Wild, Wild World: Awake at Night
event.description: At this workshop little night owls can meet several live animals who don't like bedtimes either. Rob Mies of the Organization for Bat Conservation will bring along a few of his nocturnal friends, including a two-toed sloth, barred owl, flying squirrel and a bat. Ages 4 and up.
event.sort_string: Wild, Wild World: Awake at Night

event.description: Hear the ultimate Christmas carol, and sing along with an audience-chorus of nearly 3,000 in the state-of-the-art acoustics of Avery Fisher Hall. This year’s performance casts esteemed soloists—Amanda Pabyan, Ryu-Kyung Kim, Scott Murphree, James Bobick—and 17 top NYC conductors. Ages 4 and up.

Introduce your brood to the magical world of the circus as Bello, the quirky, tuxedo-clad clown, returns to the Big Apple Circus after a nearly decade-long stint with Ringling Bros. Also on tap: a whole slew of international superstars including acrobats and puppies from Italy, trampoline and trapeze artisans from Russia, an equestrian from Kazakhstan, contortionists from China, a pyro-juggler from Spain and more. Pint-sized circus-goers will adore the intimacy of the ring: Nobody needs binoculars under this big top. All ages.
event.sort_string: Big Apple Circus: Bello Is Back!

event.description: A performer and teacher who entertains 300 preschoolers a week, Moey (Melissa Levis) sings tunes about rock stars and New York City that are sure to transport the under-ten set into a genuine tizzy. After boogying down with pom-poms, maracas and inflatable guitars, your mini-Madonna will surely hit the hay without a fuss. All ages.

Karma Kids runs a regular class for moms and their not-yet-walking charges. Today’s session bridges the gender gap as dads get a chance to stretch, pose and unwind with their tots nearby. Moms are welcome to come along to catch the frequent photo ops. Advance registration required. Ages 2 months to 2 years.

event.identifier: Brady Rymer and the Little Band That Could
event.description: The dad and roots rocker mixes folk, country, pop and blues in happy-go-lucky tunes that entice kids to get up and dance. Listen for songs from all of his CDs for tots, especially the numbers from his Grammy-nominated album, Here Comes Brady Rymer and the Little Band That Could. Ages 4 and up.
event.sort_string: Brady Rymer and The Little Band That Could

event.description: Introduce tots to the glory days of silent film at this showing of Steamboat Bill, Jr. which features the lengendary Buster Keaton’s classic gags, outrageous stunts, and trademark deadpan expression as he portrays a fresh-out-of-college bachelor trying to make good as a steamboat captain. Ages 2 and up.

Ideal for kids who think banging on pots and pans (and garbage-can lids and buckets) is more fun than playing with the latest electronic toy, Stomp is a “percussion sensation” whose cast of aerobicized dancer-musicians makes lovely noise. If you’re looking for an experience that will satisfy both a first-grader and a teen, this could be it. Ages 6 and up.
Get in the spirit of Vancouver from right here in Staten Island. Your pint-sized Olympians compete in games and create their own medals. All ages.

DeVaron performs classic kid songs, such as “Swinging on a Star” and “The Itsy Bitsy Spider,” as well as some of her own motherhood-themed originals, at the Carlyle’s weekend Madeline Tea Party for cute li’l socialites-to-be.

Join the bilingual Jose Conde Band for this special brunch edition of the popular Baby Loves Salsa event. Youngsters can groove to Spanish and English ditties such as “Mi Familia Es la Música” while munching on Cuban French toast with blackberry maple butter and sipping on kiddie mocktails like the Morir Soñando (an orange-juice milk shake with cinnamon and sugar). Ages 6 months to 6 years.

Families create paper lanterns from construction paper and tissue paper to celebrate this bright holiday. Afterwards, show off your personalized lantern in the family parade through the museum. All ages.

event.identifier: Meet the Artist: Harlem Gospel Choir
event.description: Head over to Lincoln Center for this free event (first come, first served, so get there early), which introduces youngsters to this globe-trotting ensemble, comprised of musicians from Harlem and the tri-state area. The group will deliver a performance that highlights African-American culture through inspirational music, and then hold a question and answer session for their young audience. Ages 5 and up.
event.sort_string: Meet the Artist: Harlem Gospel Choir

event.description: In this 4,00 square-foot interactive area, which includes a miniature version of New York City, kids can feed alphabet letters to a talking baby dragon, drive a fire truck, paint on a six-foot art wall, find their way through a crawling challenge course and more. Ages newborn to 4 years.
This exhibition reveals the similarities between natural modes of connection—spiderwebs and rivers, for example—and the Internet.

Interactive displays, computer animation and meterorite specimens—such as the 34-ton Ahnighito, the largest meteorite on display anywhere in the world—shed light on our 4.5 billion-year-old solar system.

On Mondays and Saturdays, the instructors at Mini Chef teach children to cook or bake a new dish. During the fall, expect treats like mini apple pies, pumpkin tarts and gingerbread cookies to be on the menu. See website for full schedule. Ages 4 and up.

Princess Fiona, Lord Farquaad and the rest of the crew from the land of Duloc hit the stage with the big green guy for a musical adventure based on William Steig’s book. While it lacks one Eddie Murphy as the lovable Donkey, the production elicits as many hearty giggles as the screen version did. Sadly, everyone’s favorite ogre will play his last Broadway show on the Great White Way this weekend. All ages.

NYC comedy group Eight Is Never Enough has been making children laugh since 2004. Audience participation is an absolute must, so if you’ve got a future member of the Upright Citizens Brigade on your hands, bring him or her here to let loose. Ages 4 and up.

In the Manhattan Children’s Theatre’s creative take on the classic Hans Christian Andersen tale, a cast of two brings to life the story of the ever-curious Little Mermaid who wants nothing more than to experience life on land. All ages.

event.identifier: Peter and the Wolf & The Frog Prince
event.description: Families can enjoy the strung-up versions of two classic tales at this double feature. First, Peter and the Wolf tells the story of a clever little boy who captures a dangerous wolf. Then, in The Frog Prince, a princess finds her suitor in the form of an amphibian. Ages 3 and up.
event.sort_string: Peter and the Wolf & the Frog Prince

event.description: The Pied Piper Children’s Theatre of NYC presents this musical by Elliott Baker. Expect lots of music and dancing to wow little onlookers. All ages.
FasTracKids is a place where kids mix playtime with learning critical skills for school and life, such as problem solving, public speaking, decision-making, leadership and teamwork.

event.identifier: Valentine's Special: Molten Chocolate Sweethearts Workshop
event.description: Give your young bakers a reason to absorb some French lessons: at this Valentine’s Day-inspired workshop, kids learn to bake the heart-shaped cakes, adorned with raspberry Chantilly, fresh raspberries and silver pearls. Ages 5 to 11.
event.sort_string: Valentine's Special: Molten Chocolate Sweethearts Workshop

event.description: The playful display features childhood artifacts dating from the past 200 years, including antique toys, teddy bears and the Stettheimer Dollhouse, all of which were once owned by real New Yorkers.

event.identifier: Basically Brandenburg with the Symphony Space All-Stars
event.description: Distinguished musicians from around NYC play Bach’s Brandenburg Concertos, a collection of six works given to Christian Ludwig in the 1700s. Families can enjoy hearing the classic pieces played together, and picking out which arrangements they recognize. All ages.
event.sort_string: Basically Brandenburg with the Symphony Space All-Stars

event.description: You and your brood may change the lyrics of “Dancing in the Street” to “Dancing on the Ice” at this skate night that pays tribute to the music that came out of Detroit in the 1960s. And with all those good vibes, maybe your youngster will be able to loosen his grip from the wall and skate. All ages.

The youth theater’s intimate stage transforms into the belly of the New York City’s subway system, crawling with thespian rats and mummies. During the jazz-inspired musical, the players reveal the mystery behind the acronym. Ages 3 to 12.

Dance meets drumming at this multicultural show featuring companies specializing in flamenco, Irish step dancing, clogging and more. Presented by Gotham Arts Exchange, the performance is sure to have your kids boogying in their seats, and maybe even begging for a pair of tap shoes. All ages.

event.identifier: Nai-Ni Chen Dance Company presents Year of the Tiger
event.description: Celebrate the Chinese New Year with Jersey native Nai-Ni Chen’s seamlessly choreographed blend of both traditional and contemporary music and dance. The vibrant celebration showcases dancing ribbons, dragons and martial arts in honor of the big cat. Ages 8 and up.
event.sort_string: Nai-Ni Chen Dance Company presents Year of the Tiger

event.description: Between the sword-pierced necks and the vanishing fingers, this weekly performance will appeal to your kids’ most macabre instincts. The long-running magic show features a rotating cast of the city’s best prestidigitators; check website for the current lineup. Ages 10 and up.

Treat the tots to this gratis concert of West-African sounds. Griot— poet and wandering musician—Famoro Dioubate will delight youngsters as he plays the balafon, or xylophone, a popular instrument in West Africa since the 1200s. All ages.

event.identifier: Young Reader Book Club Meeting: Harriet the Spy
event.description: There is a reason that more than 45 years after its original publication, Louise Fitzhugh’s Harriet the Spy continues to inspire little notebook-carrying snoops throughout the streets of New York. Your curious tot can tag along with Harriet, Golly and Sport, and should come ready to discuss their sneaky adventures with future spies and bookworms alike. Snacks provided. Ages 8 to 12.
event.sort_string: Young Reader Book Club Meeting: Harriet the Spy

event.description: Acrobatic exhibitionist troupe Cirque du Soleil brings back its children’s offering for another run in the city. The show recounts a boy’s journey from a town without snow to a fictionalized arctic circle filled with giant characters made from ice. Acrobatic numbers are interwoven with games, dances and enormous marionettes posing as fantastical wintry creatures. All ages.

Explore the shapes, colors and patterns found at the Cathedral. Using hands-on activities, arts and crafts and stories, kids can observe architecture, stained glass, and art and then create their own pieces to take home. Ages 2 to 4.

This folksinger has three children’s albums under her guitar strap, and in each she sings about girly pastimes and mystical themes. If your youngster’s current obsession has anything to do with hairbrushes, fairies, the moon or mermaids, this kiddie concert is a can’t-miss. Ages 3 and up.

Time Out Kids fave Bari Koral rocks this concert benefiting the Brownstone School. The group also has reason to celebrate—they’re releasing their first full-length disc, Rock and Roll Garden. Kids will bop around to catchy tunes and family-friendly lyrics that zero in on children’s favorite topics—like farm animals, surfing and “Dad’s New Car.” Ages 1 to 6.

text.content: Advance tickets $15, children $12, babies free; day of show $18, children $15, babies free

event.description: Margery Williams' tale about a stuffed rabbit may be one of your tot's current favorites; in this original play two adult brothers find their old copy of the popular book as they pack up their family home, taking them on a nostalgic journey back into childhood. In the lively show, your kid can see that the little bunny who longs to be “real,” is meaningful to many children and grown-ups alike. Ages 4 and up.
The boys’ and girls’ choir performs classical holiday favorites (from Bach to Palestrina) and traditional Hispanic folk songs. All ages.

Kids can take a gander at some of the more colorful creatures in the animal kingdom, and learn about how different hues help animals to camouflage themselves from predators, attract mates and survive in the wild. Then youngsters will create a craft, access their wild side for dramatic play and meet some of the animals. Ages 3 to 6.

text.content: $20, includes zoo admission for one child and one adult

event.description: The landmarks featured in NYBG’s wildly popular diorama—including the Brooklyn Bridge and the Statue of Liberty—are made entirely out of plant-based materials such as twigs, acorns and berries. New to this year’s show is a replica of the original Pennsylvania Station, a Beaux Arts building that was dismantled in the 1960s to make room for Madison Square Garden. Tickets must be purchased in advance. All ages.

text.content: $20, seniors and students $18, children ages 2 to 12 $10, under 2 free; November 21-January 10 adults $25, seniors and students $22, children ages 2 to 12 $15, under 2 free

event.description: Indie rock kiddie-style is what you’ll get when you check out tot-band the Jimmies. Fun, catchy and even educational, the tunes from their latest album, Make Your Own Someday, are ideal mood boosters for a chilly January morning. Ages 1 and up.

text.content: Advance tickets $18, children under 12 $12; day of show $19, children under 12 $13

event.description: With coaching by dance educator Ellen Robbins, children have created engaging dance works that range from hilarious to abstract to dramatic. The pieces will be danced by peers of the choreographers, ranging in age from 8 to 18. All ages.

Strap an apron on your little one and drop her off at this single-session version of the Y’s popular cooking class. Even if your little chef isn’t hungry enough to eat the edibles made in the lesson, she can enjoy a storytime and take the treats home for a late-night snack. Ages 2 to 5.

Check out New York’s take on an ancient winter art form—sword dancing. Performers will show off their fancy footwork and skill with sharp objects as they perform fast-paced rapper dances, long sword dances, and other complex and intricate steps with blades. All ages.

Skip the mercury-laden tuna rolls and get a different taste of Japan: Native musicians and performers will beat on an array of ancestral taiko drums and play bamboo flutes. After the pros have presented a few of their original tunes, kids can leave their seats to try out some of the instruments. All ages.

The Museum at Eldridge Street’s annual family concert showcases clarinetist Greg Wall and his band Klezmerfest as they lead a musical tour of Eastern European Jewish culture. In the grand finale, the audience enacts a shtetl wedding with kids taking on the roles of bride, groom and wedding guests. Reservations recommended. All ages.

event.identifier: Sunday Science Spectacular: Plate Tectonics and Moving Continents
event.description: This lesson is way more exciting than your tyke’s humdrum school science class. Kids learn about our ever-moving earth and what happens when continents shift (the answer: earthquakes and volcanic eruptions). Then young scientists make “lava”-spewing mountains. Ages 6 to 11.
event.sort_string: Sunday Science Spectacular: Plate Tectonics and Moving Continents

event.description: This year, for the first time Le Carrousel, Bryant Park’s 14-animal merry-go-round, will remain open throughout the fall and winter; after your kids go for a ride they can catch an appearance by this storytelling amphibian (portrayed by New Yorker Dan Kitrosser). Expect winter- and holiday-related performances, including “Flaubert’s Great Big Snowball Fight” and “Flaubert’s New Year’s Resolutions, 2010.” All ages.

Monkey see, monkey do. This insightful doc, part of the PBS “Nature Series,” celebrates anything and everything about the fuzzy, banana-eating mammals. And while you and your tots are ooohing over the cute factor, you’ll be learning about primate communication and family life. Ages 5 and up.

Literally Alive Children’s Theatre presents a musical twist on the classic holiday tale about a Christmas-hating grouch whose bah-humbug life is rerouted by a visit from the ghosts of Christmas past, present and future. Arrive an hour early for a preshow art workshop, in which families get to meet the cast, listen to a live percussion trio and make a craft. Ages 3 and up.

Put the kids in their PJs and head over to the Y for a Shabbat wind-down. Children will get to smell spices, watch candles glow, and munch on cookies and milk. Director of Jewish Arts and Culture Karina Zilberman leads a sing-along session. All ages.

At this new family program, museum educators lead tours and art workshops that adhere to a specific theme. Today, kids and parents will think about how artists turn ideas into works of art; then they’ll apply their newfound knowledge to a hands-on project. Ages 6 to 10.
Start off your family’s visit at this second-floor exhibition, which presents an introduction to the region’s artwork—where, why and how it’s made, as well as the all-important “What’s going on?”

event.identifier: Celebrate Losar: The Tibetan New Year
event.description: The museum celebrates Losar, Tibet’s most important holiday, with a weekend lineup including tea and fire ceremonies and a sacred dance. Check the website for a full schedule of events, including discussions on these and other Tibetan cultural traditions. Ages 10 and up.

text.content: $5, seniors and students $3, children under 6 free

event.sort_string: Celebrate Losar: The Tibetan New Year

event.identifier: New York City Ballet Presents Jewels
event.description: Balanchine conjures up the quarry with this blinging production consisting of three dances: Emeralds, Rubies, and Diamonds. Your little one will get an eyefull of costumes that reflect these stones in outrageous puffs of tulle and shimmering stones. With music by Fauré, Stravinsky and Tchaikovsky, your family is bound to leave with eyes that sparkle. Ages 8 and up.
event.sort_string: New York City Ballet Presents Jewels

event.description: Based on the beloved 2000 movie, this musical-theater sensation, which swept the 2009 Tony Awards, boasts the same scriptwriter (Lee Hall) and director (Stephen Daldry) as the flick. Pop icon Elton John contributed the anthem and ballad-heavy score. The underdog tale follows the title character (played on alternate nights by three übertalented teens), a boy in a hard-bitten family of miners in Northern England who dreams of becoming a ballet dancer. Ages 8 and up.

Purim is just around the corner, so have your little ones learn to make the mascot dish of the holiday, hamantaschen, triangular pastries with jam filling. Then take the tasty treats home to share with the rest of the family. Ages 2 to 5.

This annual holiday celebration features ice skating performances by children and instructors from the Sky Rink Skating School, including Sky Rink’s top US and regional competitors. Limit two tickets per person. All ages.
Budding fashion designers will love this Project Runway-esque workshop hosted by Little Bird, where tots can create flashy tees and glittery hair accessories for the holidays. All ages.

This evening is dedicated entirely to magic & comedy in a show that will bring your family to the very limits of its imagination. Currently the longest running magic show in Queens, Evenings of Wonder boasts some of the most skilled magicians, manipulators, jugglers and other performers in the city, who will take stage to astound babes. Expect many “How do they do that?” inquiries for your tots post-performance. All ages.

In honor of Martin Luther King Day, kids design personalized pins that symbolize their support for equal rights. They will also be able to weave friendship bracelets out of yarn and illustrate the story of Rosa Parks using markers and pencils. All ages.

Prepare to be wowed as the members of this circus company (consisting of pros from Soleil, Moscow and others) show off their aerial ability. Watch as a punch of inspiration turns a gaggle of everyday assembly workers into a colorful crew of flighty acrobats, dancers, contortionists and clowns. Ooohs and Aaahs guaranteed for kids and grown-ups alike. Ages 4 and up.
Gather at Le Carrousel to see master magicians enrapture youngsters with sophisticated tricks and sleight-of-hand stunners. All ages.

Unlike much comedic fare, this weekly event is appropriate for the whole family. That means lots of warnings about clean language from the referee, who keeps two competing comic improv teams in check and invites audience participation. Ages 8 and up.

Learn the art of paper sculpting from the best. This world-renowned paper artist teaches the basics of folding, cutting, sculpting and decorating the most basic medium with glitter, oil pastels and pipe cleaners. Ages 5 and up.

Cartooning is made easy in this interactive class with Jason Bryant, known for his realistic portraits that seem to jump from the canvas. The artist will create a cutout of each kid’s favorite cartoon, then it’s up to the little ones to personalize the drawing with details. The hardest part may be deciding on just one favorite character. Ages 3 to 10.

Tots can learn about the string family, including the violin, viola, cello and bass, of a traditional symphonic orchestra. Members of the Queens Symphony Orchestra are on hand to give musical demonstrations of each instrument. All ages.
The Manhattan Kids Guide hosts an afternoon of holiday refreshments, live entertainment and free raffles for family gifts. All ages.

Looking for something to do with the family on a lazy Sunday? Try hitting this weekly fair at P.S. 116, which peddles vintage kid clothing, children’s books, handcrafted jewelry, and an assortment of goodies like pastries and flavored olive oils made by nabe residents. All ages.

event.identifier: Irma and Paul Milstein Family Hall of Ocean Life
event.description: This is the home of the famous life-size model of a blue whale.
event.sort_string: Irma and Paul Milstein Family Hall of Ocean Life

event.description: Class clowns finally get an appropriate venue: At this showcase, local cutups ages 12 to 18 perform their own comedy routines at the famous Chelsea club. Brave audience members also get the chance to go onstage and try out their own jokes. Ages 9 and up.

Get ready for an afternoon of silliness on the high seas when you take in a showing of Gilbert and Sullivan’s opera about a captain’s daughter who falls in love with a lowly sailor. At a workshop before the show (at 1:45pm), kids can interact with the New York Gilbert & Sullivan Players’ artistic director, Albert Bergeret, as he discusses the show’s history, plot and music. Youngsters may even put on a sailor’s getup and learn a few of the classic songs themselves. All ages.

With Finian's Rainbow on Broadway, the time is ripe for another Yip Harburg revival, this time of his satirical 1951 Christmas musical (written with Fred Saidy and Sammy Fain) that mocked the McCarthy hearings via an allegory about conflict in the toy industry. Keith Lee Grant directs an abridged version. Ages 8 and up.

Sponsored by the New York Mets, this exhibit reveals the science underlying various sports—such as why baseballs soar and surfboards don’t sink. Kids can enjoy live demonstrations and test their tennis, baseball, surfing, drag-racing and rock-climbing skills.

Composer John Bertles and his invented-instrument ensemble wield such unlikely and inviting implements as pots, pans and a marimba made of cat-food cans. In this session, kids will learn about the wind section of an orchestra. Ages 3 to 6.

The Altar Boyz have their own definition of soul music: They sing about Jesus in the unlikely idiom of boy-band pop. The plot of this well-wrought mock concert is communion-wafer thin, but the show’s young stars really work their crosses off. Ages 10 and up.

Anime and pirate fans alike relish this retro Hayao Miyazaki gem, which was released before the Japanese director’s Spirited Away and My Neighbor Totoro shot to megafame status. In Miyazaki’s version of the Robert Louis Stevenson classic, the protagonists are a young boy and girl who encounter a feline Long John Silver and a crew of pirate pigs on their search for treasure. Ages 3 to 8.

event.identifier: “Give the Gift of the Arts” Holiday Show
event.description: This holiday show includes performances by Harlem School of the Art’s students and faculty members, The HSA Jazz Ensemble, and works by the Visual Arts department. All ages.
event.sort_string: Give the Gift of the Arts Holiday Show

event.description: Set to Tchaikovsky’s soaring score, this romantic tale of love and forgiveness is often considered the world’s most beloved ballet. Consequently, we’re confident it’s an ideal introduction to dance for uninitiated youngsters. With breathtaking choreography, lavish costumes and abstract designs by Per Kirkeby, New York City Ballet's production is visually enchanting enough to capture the attention of restless kids. Ages 6 and up.

event.identifier: The Rose Center for Earth and Space
event.description: The space-age wing includes the Hayden Planetarium. Exhibits are text-heavy, but kids may enjoy running down the Cosmic Pathway—a spiral ramp representing the 13 billion years since the big bang.
event.sort_string: Rose Center for Earth and Space

event.description: Kids squish, roll and braid challah dough; the baking will happen at their own homes. They also get to sing along with Karina Zilberman, director of Jewish arts and culture at the Y. All ages.

If your little one can keep his eyes open until midnight, treat him to a spectacle that will make them pop. As the clock rings in a new decade, bursts of color will splash the night sky. Arrive early to snag a prime viewing spot and a delicious (and free) hot beverage. All ages.

In this fairy-tale hybrid, the Big Bad Wolf strives to prove that he’s “good,” not “bad,” as he travels through a trifecta of fables: “The Three Pigs,” “Three Billy Goats Gruff” and “The Three Bears.” With the help of, that’s right, three blind mice (and the audience), the world’s most conniving canine struggles to reinvent himself. Ages 3 to 9.

event.identifier: The Lahjan Tytöt Aesthetic Gymnastics Club Present Aladdin
event.description: Your youngsters can watch in awe as this Finnish group performs the story of Aladdin, through a combination of modern dance, gymnastics and folk songs. All ages.
event.sort_string: Lahjan Tytöt Aesthetic Gymnastics Club Present Aladdin

event.description: This North Carolina–based dad brings his parent-approved hip-hop beats to the city that never sleeps (except for crucial naptimes). Listen for tunes from his Grammy-nominated album, Easy, as your tot bops to songs about dragons, mermaids and robots. All ages.

text.content: Advance tickets $18, children under 12 $12; at the door $19, children under 12 $13

event.identifier: Chinese New Year! with Grace Chang
event.description: Ring in the Year of the Tiger with a magical touch at this celebration, featuring children’s author and former Chinese circus performer Grace Chang. She’ll perform a dazzling mix of enchanted illusions, puppetry, and ventriloquism with some help from Jin Jin the Dragon, the star of her children's book series. Ages 3 to 8.
event.sort_string: Chinese New Year! with Grace Chang

event.description: Natalie Cronin Reyes, Kidville's National Early Childhood Development Director and Ofrit Peres of Unplugged on a Rug for a morning dedicated to teaching kids how to reuse, reduce and recycle. All proceeds benefit The Max Cure Foundation. Reservations recommended. Ages 1 to 4.

event.identifier: Junior Science Club: Seeing Isn’t Always Believing
event.description: Tweens study the science of optical illusions and invent their own mind tricks. Ages 8 to 13.
event.sort_string: Junior Science Club: Seeing Isn’t Always Believing

event.description: Kids will explore exactly how they process auditory stimuli, from classical and popular music to the sounds of nature. As they engage in listening exercises, youngsters are encouraged to record what they hear through drawing, writing poems and transribing their reactions into notebooks. All ages.

Rock Center Café’s executive chef Antonio Prontelli whips up a family-style breakfast of pancakes, scrambled eggs, breakfast wraps, bacon and other treats for kids to nosh on alongside old Saint Nick. Guests will receive a holiday basket filled with warm gingerbread and candy canes, a skating session and a present from Santa himself. Space fills up fast, so reserve your spot in advance. All ages.
Get your tots ready for the festivities of this Jewish holiday by creating costumes, masks, and noisemakers. Youngsters can also try their hand at illustrating a Purim scroll. Ages 5 to 12.

Who says all bulls have to be aggressive and all gentle beasts have to be boring? Not Ferdinand, that’s for sure. Take your tots to enjoy this puppet show performed by the Hudson Vagabond Puppets Company, based on Munro Leaf’s charming children’s book of the same name. Featuring an impressive cast of puppets including the bull who doesn’t want to fight, talking flowers and a turtle, this show will make kids into lovers, not fighters. Ages 4 to 10.

In honor of the legendary choreographer’s birthday, the New York City Ballet presents a selection of works inspired by the three countries that stirred him most. On the lineup are Walpurgisnacht Ballet, which Balanchine based on a scene from the French composer Charles Gounod’s opera Faust, and two new ballets: one choreographed by Peter Martins and influenced by the United States, the other choreographed by Alexey Miroshnichenko and influenced by Russia. Ages 8 and up.

event.identifier: The Little Engine That Could Puppet Show
event.description: This whimsical take on the classic tale about a positive-thinking little locomotive is the brainchild of NYC puppet master Ralph Lee. Featuring old-fashioned steam engine puppets with their own quirky personalities, it’s sure to inspire many rousing rounds of the “I think I can, I think I can” mantra. Railroad-crazed tots can even snag a photo with another famous train, Thomas the Tank Engine, and (from January 2 through 10) meet Sir Topham Hatt. Ages 2 to 7.
event.sort_string: Little Engine That Could Puppet Show

event.description: Wind down from New Year’s celebrations by catching a screening of this Kermit and Piggy classic. The movie-musical follows the Muppet gang as they try to make it on Broadway. Have your tots keep their eyes peeled for a scene in which Fozzy, Gonzo et al. are wee babes; the sequence launched the popular Muppet Babies series. All ages.

This ode to soap was created by Fan Yang, 16-time Guinness record holder for blowing the biggest soap bubble, and it features the full spectrum of his artistry. This program includes magic, lighting effects and…bubbles: giant bubbles, walls of bubbles, bubbles within bubbles. If you have any little Pigpens running around, perhaps this show will convey soap’s allure. Ages 5 and up.

At the 25th annual Special Camp Fair, parents of kids and teens with special needs can start planning out their summer fun with the help of representatives from 70 NYC-area day camps and Northeast sleepaway camps. Parents can also learn about travel programs, early childhood programs, and volunteer and job opportunities. All ages.

In this musical version of the Brothers Grimm tale, a three-person cast gets kids laughing. The amphibian, who wears rubber gloves for ears and becomes a prince in the play’s final moments, even ventures into the audience to coax smiles from children. Ages 4 and up.

We know what you’re thinking: Don’t you mean sapphire nuts? Emerald is the healthy-snack brand sponsoring the event, not the color of the runners’ frigid cojones. While joggers ring in the New Year with a four-mile loop, family members of all ages can view spectacular fireworks and join in the fun with music, dancing and a grand costume parade at the Bandshell, where the race begins and ends. Midnight runners pay $30–$45 entry fee. All ages.

event.identifier: The Journey of Blues to New York City
event.description: Ready to get the blues? Harlem’s legendary artist Keith “The Captain” Gamble, along with his ensemble, will take you and your audophile brood on a musical journey from the deep South to the Big Apple, tracing how the this musical form developed from the African-American work songs and spirituals of yore to the jazz and rock inflected music of today. All ages.
event.sort_string: Journey of Blues to New York City

event.description: Join the zookeepers for a tour of the animal kitchen, where kids can help prepare seasonal chow for critters before watching them gobble it up. Little ones will be treated to a breakfast snack of their own. Preregistration required. Ages 5 and up.

It won’t knock your socks off, but this sweet musical revival (the original was a downtown staple for 42 years before closing in 2002) features a memorable score that drama-obsessed tweens should hear performed. It tells the zany story of two young lovers who find romance at the hands of their meddling fathers but soon realize that love isn’t all it’s cracked up to be. Ages 8 and up.

After a Christmas is story is read aloud, kids will gather around to craft their holiday letters to ol' Saint Nick. After applying stickers and other snazzy decorations, the letters will be mailed off to the North Pole. All ages.
Families can get a tour of the current exhibition at BRIC and then create their own artwork using various materials. All ages.

Prep for the much-anticipated Burton film adaptation of the classic Lewis Carroll story with this colorful staged version. Kids enjoy the whimsical costumes and music, while mom and pop can ponder the shadowy references to gated communities, protective parents and fear of the unknown. Select Saturday matinee variations include teen members of the Young Company of Brooklyn. Audience size is limited, so purchasing tickets in advance is recommended. Ages 10 and up.

We dig an offbeat family tradition. For this annual avian census, volunteers of all ages fan out with binoculars and guidebooks to help conservationists track the long-term health of populations. “Mommy, remember the year we spotted a chickadee?!?” is so much sweeter than recollections of gifts big or small, dontcha think? All ages.

Steve Cohen, the Millionaires’ Magician, conjures up an intimate evening of parlor magic at the Waldorf-Astoria. Since shows are limited to 50 guests, your kid is guaranteed an up-close view of Cohen’s mind reading and trickery. Ages 10 and up.

New mamas stretch their limbs, strengthen their tired tummies and then give their babies a turn to follow suit. With mother’s hand to guide them, infants (from newbies to babes just learning to walk) engage in gentle yoga poses. The event is a chance to test out Karma Kids’ weekly class of the same name. Ages 8 weeks to 18 months.

Get into the “Feliz Navidad” spirit with the infectious Latin stylings of Zon del Barrio. Your kids will be salsa dancing in their seats as the band performs updated renditions of traditional Puerto Rican aguinaldos, or Christmas carols, that are heavy on guitar, tambourine and maracas. All ages.

event.identifier: The Melodious Master: The Life and Music of Fauré
event.description: Let cellist Steven Isserlis change the way your kiddos feel about classical music with this witty hour-long musical portrait of French composer Gabriel Fauré. Isserlis is the author of a number of music-themed children’s books, including Why Beethoven Threw the Stew and Why Handel Wagged His Wig. Ages 6 to 10.
event.sort_string: Melodious Master: The Life and Music of Faure

event.identifier: New York City Ballet Presents All Robbins
event.description: Tales of community are danced in a tribute to Jerome Robbins, pioneer of both the ballet and Broadway stages. Dances at a Gathering offers a naturalistic look into human relationships; the West Side Story suite takes a more colorful approach with a throwback to the vibrant city streets of the 1950’s. And although the city certainly has changed since the days of the Jets and Sharks, there’s no reason why you and your brood can’t dance along the pavement post-production. Ages 8 and up.
event.sort_string: New York City Ballet Presents All Robbins

event.description: In this new musical take on the canonical fairy tale, Cinderella is a smart cookie who uses cleverness and kindness to get to the Prince’s ball. At the free preshow arts workshop (one hour before every performance), kids will learn about the original literary origins of the story and how the theater company brought it to the stage. Ages 3 and up.

Hosted by the Urban Divers, this event teaches kids all about owls: What they eat, where they live and who they are. Kids will meet an owl from the urban watershed, and then participate in a hands-on activity. All ages.

This Brooklyn-based photographer was once an editor for mega-publisher CondeNast, but has now focused her time snapping shots of local cutie pies as well as tots all over the country. Her photos reflect the editor in her, as she sets up her shoots like she used to produce her stories: lots of attention to detail and styled to play up the tot's unique personality, each photo evoking a sweet, vintage feeling.

The title of this event may sound pretty darn girly, but boys are welcome too. Traditionally known in Japan as a time to wish for the health and happiness of young women, this afternoon features workshops in which kids can participate in decorating ceremonial dolls with peach blossoms and make their own hina dolls to take home. Families can also munch on festival-related snacks, including rice cakes wrapped in cherry leaf, and listen to springtime songs performed on the stringed koto instrument. Ages 3 to 10.
Hear local storyteller Asante perform AfroCaribbean folk tales accompanied by percussive beats. Your little ones shouldn't be surprised if they're asked to get up and dance! All ages.

Let Uncle Rock—a.k.a. Robert Burke Warren, former bassist of the late-’70s punk group the Fleshtones—do what his name implies: get your kids moving to his country-infused rockabilly tunes. Today, kids will hear brand-new songs from the The Big Picture, the crooner's newest disc that pays tribute to the likes of David Bowie, the Rolling Stones and Johnny Cash. Ages 2 to 10.

event.identifier: Kids in the Kitchen with Grandparents
event.description: Tots mix, stir and taste delicious recipes with their nanas and pop-pops at their sides. If they don’t feel like chowing down on the spot, wee ones can enjoy a storytime instead and take their treats home to Mom and Dad. Ages 2 to 5.
event.sort_string: Kids in the Kitchen with Grandparents

event.description: Take in an afternoon of old-fashioned melodrama, Gilbert and Sullivan style. Kids should expect to see plenty of virtuous maidens, hardy sailors and dastardly barons belting out catchy tunes. Before the show (at 1:45pm), the New York Gilbert & Sullivan Players’ artistic director, Albert Bergeret, will discuss the opera’s plot, music and history. All ages.

text.content: $40-$96, children under 13 get in for half price

event.description: This German version of “Snow White” features more or less the same characters as the English one, with a king in search of a wife; Mr. 7-Dwarf, who encompasses all of the traditional seven dwarfs’ traits; and—spoiler alert—a happy ending in typical boy-gets-girl fashion. Ages 3 and up.

This etiquette class will cover topics like setting the table, proper use of utensils, glassware and dishes, behavior and attire at the table, mealtime conversation and other tips pertinent to holiday festivities. RSVP required. Ages 4 and up.

If your tot has an obsession with adorable beasts, then maybe the zoo is the place to be on V-Day. She can make a love-themed craft for mom and dad, then pose with one of the zoo's education animals for a photo. All ages.

This holiday musical follows Iggy the Elf, who has just been given his own TV show by Santa for his appearance on “Prancing with the Stars”. Along with lots of laughter, kids can expect opportunities for audience participation during the performance. All ages.

Tots are invited to sing along with this musical adventure, performed by the Poppy Seed Players, a group that performs kid-friendly musicals about Jewish heritage in the big apple. In this colorful number, Queen Esther saves the Jews of Shushan, sentenced to death by the King. All ages.

event.identifier: National Dance Institute Presents Imagine: A Celebration of John Lennon
event.description: During the 2008–9 school year, thousands of young dancers who were enrolled at NDI learned about John Lennon’s life, art and music. The lessons culminated in May and June, when the kids danced to the late Beatle’s songs in more than 70 shows across the city. At this special encore performance (which also serves as a benefit for NDI), the troupe will shimmy and shake to “Help!,” “Come Together” and, of course, “Imagine.” Ages 4 and up.
event.sort_string: National Dance Institute Presents Imagine: A Celebration of John Lennon

event.description: Musicians from the Queens Symphony Orchestra teach tots about the instruments that make up the woodwind family of a traditional symphonic orchestra. Your family will hear demonstrations of the flute, oboe, clarinet and bassoon. All ages.

In this musical take on Tomie de Paola’s kid-lit fave Strega Nona, the titular friendly witch tries to solve all of the problems of her teensy Italian town of Calabria, from the baker’s bunions to the local singletons’ unlucky love lives. But when the clumsy Big Anthony messes with her magic pasta pot and can’t seem to turn it off, Strega Nona has to act fast. Can she save Calabria from a carbo-loaded fate? Ages 3 and up.

event.identifier: Little Orchestra Society presents Magic, Music and Mystery
event.description: Renowned illusionist Lyn Dillies performs visual tricks and vanishing acts, including making a man disappear and reappear inside a glass case. Dino Anagnost, who has served as conductor at the Society since 1979, leads an orchestra in accompanying selections from Modest Mussorgsky’s “Pictures at an Exhibition” and Edvard Grieg’s Peer Gynt Suites. Ages 6 to 12.
event.sort_string: Little Orchestra Society presents Magic, Music and Mystery

event.description: This play area for children 3 and up offers a toddler play area, arcade and redemption games as well as a cafe. The three story space becomes brag-wrothy with their triple slide, mazes, obstacle course, lookout bubble and more. Themed birthday parties in private party rooms are also available, as well as Mommy and Me classes in English, Polish and Spanish.

Join BAX’s regular MC, Jumpin’ Juniper, the 100-year-old tree-sprite alter ego of actress Joanna Walchuk, as she hosts a sing-along of musical-theater tunes, dubbed Broadway Bound, with Leigh Stein. After the singing, kids can hang out in a staffed, indoor play space full of toys. Ages 2 and up.

text.content: $15 per adult/child pair, $8 per additional child, children under 2 free

event.description: What will it be: six more weeks of winter or an early spring? Watch Staten Island’s cutest weather predictor, Chuck, come out of his burrow and decide. With an 85 percent accuracy rate, his word may do you more good than the Weather Channel’s. Stick around for a breakfast with the furry forecaster for an additional fee ($10, children under 5 $5). All ages.

event.identifier: “On the Streets: New York's Trolleys and Buses.”
event.description: In this trove of artifacts from the city’s above-ground transportation system, you’ll see a 1960s bus, a child-size trolley and a facsimile of a traffic intersection.
event.sort_string: “On the Streets: New York's Trolleys and Buses.”

event.description: Combining guitar, sax, bass and percussion with songs in a variety of foreign languages (plus English), Hot Peas ’N Butter brings multiculturalism to the young masses. Ages 3 to 11.

event.identifier: Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. Celebration
event.description: Honor the legacy of Dr. King at this evening celebrating the civil-rights legend. Children get to listen to a performance by Smokie Norful, a gospel heavyweight who’s garnered a Grammy win for his tunes. Ages 12 and up.
event.sort_string: Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. Celebration

event.description: Inspire your future engineers at this full day of robot mania, courtesy of the RoBo Cup international initiative, which educates students in technology through robotics challenges. Watch the pros create androids that dance and play soccer. Ages 6 and up.

Colorful floats, cooperative camels, ebullient schoolchildren and 12-foot-tall puppets descend on Spanish Harlem for this holiday procession honoring the Magi’s visit to that famous manger. Expect plenty of live music at the parade, which is cosponsored by El Museo del Barrio and the Museum of the City of New York. A festival follows on the afternoon Jan 10 at El Museo del Barrio, featuring Latin American songs, dance performances, interactive games and prizes. All ages.
WIRED editor Ken Denmead and Assistant Editor Matt Blum lead kids and their dads in LEGO build challenges and other projects from the magazine's blog. Ages 3 to 12.
Tykes can carve a block of limestone, create illuminated letters, design gargoyles and learn weaving techniques at the uptown cathedral. Ages 4 and up.

This Lincoln Center production is the one people have in mind when they ask, “Have you been to The Nutcracker ?” The New York City Ballet’s full roster of 150 ballerinas, danseurs and musicians—plus 50 children from the School of American Ballet—perform Balanchine’s classic choreography. Princess-smitten tots are most likely to fall for the Sugar Plum Fairy and the Snow Queen, but all kids will get a kick out of the one-ton Christmas tree that “grows” onstage, and Mother Ginger, who hides little dancers under her nine-foot-wide skirt. Ages 5 and up.
This live production of the classic fairy tale comes complete with wicked stepsisters, a dazzling ball, a charming prince and, of course, magic. Ages 3 and up.
The Zoo’s Clydesdale horses Ranger, Jesse, and Monty take wee passengers (and their parents!) on festive wagon rides during the weekends through December. All ages.

The pitch-perfectly performed show is one of only a few adult (i.e. non-Disney branded) musicals on Broadway that is entirely appropriate for children. There’s no death, no heartbreak, no sex; just feel-good vibes, sunshine, laughing, kissing, singing, magic and yes, a rainbow. As has been noted in countless other publications, the score (by Burton Lane and Yip Harburg) is a dream, the choreography (by director Warren Carlyle) is fresh and joyful, and the cast (particularly leads Kate Baldwin, Cheyenne Jackson and Jim Norton) is masterful. There’s just one small problem. The story in Finian’s Rainbow may actually be too maudlin for certain, smart aleck kids, not to mention their jaded parents. Those without an appetite for corn, beware!
Families can rock out with kiddie entertainer Ms. Janis, who celebrates the release of her CD “Miss Janis, Music and Me: Moving Bodies and Inspiring Hearts” with holiday tunes. All ages.

text.content: $10 in advance per child/adult pair, $5 per additional child, $15 at the door

event.description: Julliard-trained violinist Meg Okura introduces the sound of the ancient Chinese fiddle, the erhu, delivering a pan-Asian flavored mix of classical, jazz and world music. The string musician has performed alongside such hotshots as David Bowie and Kanye West. All ages.
Kids can decorate a cookie house with holiday trimmings including candy, sprinkles, and sugar pop-ons. All ages.

The 13th Street Rep presents its musical adaptation of “Rumpelstiltskin.” Also check the schedule for intermittent productions of Imagination Show, the Rep’s highly interactive clown act. Ages 5 and up.

Cobble Hill Cinemas continues its series of acclaimed flicks this month: today, Tchaikovsky’s The Nutcracker gets an avant-garde twist in A Hard Nut, featuring choreography by Mark Morris, a 1960s suburban setting and retro-chic costumes. All ages.
This quick, free reading, courtesy of a Barefoot Bookstore staff member, provides a nice respite from the inevitable headache that comes with shopping at the midtown toy emporium. Ages 5 and under.

event.identifier: The New York Theatre Ballet’s Nutcracker
event.description: Take your tiny dancers to marvel at this ballet classic; tailored to kids, the live performance has been whittled down to a single, digestible hour. Now marking its 25th consecutive year in New York City, the show continues to please audiences with its dreamlike scenes. Ages 5 and up.
FasTracKids is a place where kids mix playtime with learning critical skills for school and life, such as problem solving, public speaking, decision-making, leadership and teamwork.

In this fantastical adventure, a Wicked Wizard heads to the North Pole with nefarious plans to ruin Christmas. Catching on to the evil plot, Eddie the Elf hops aboard a sleigh and races to save Santa—and lots of presents—in this musical comedy. Ages 4 to 10.

The 2008 Tony winner for Best New Musical chronicles a single weekend in Washington Heights, showing how the neighborhood’s tight-knit Latino community approaches life and love. Written by composer (and New York native) Lin-Manuel Miranda, the production grooves to a salsa, merengue and hip-hop score; Javier Muñoz has taken over the lead role of Usnavi. Ages 8 and up.

In the history-infused kids’ book Chachaji’s Cup, a first-generation American boy learns about his Indian heritage by listening to his great-uncle tell stories. See the work presented as a one-act musical in this show. Ages 5 and up.

event.identifier: Chestnuts Roasting on the Flaming Idiots
event.description: The Flaming Idiots’ zany antics will surely tickle your family’s funny bones. Kids (and adults, too) will giggle and gasp as Gyro, Pyro and Walter bounce between crazy feats and gross goofs, all while tossing around plenty of wisecracks. All ages.
event.sort_string: Chestnuts Roasting on the Flaming Idiots

event.identifier: Grand Central Scramble Family Scavenger Hunt
event.description: Watson Adventures leads an elaborate hunt where kids and adults uncover the secrets of the world’s most famous train station: mysterious markings in the constellation ceiling, a “ghost train” and more. Children will learn a little about history, art and acoustics with which they can later astound their friends. Advance tickets required.Ages 7 and up.
event.sort_string: Grand Central Scramble Family Scavenger Hunt

event.description: Celebrate family traditions from around the world as kids explore the “World Brooklyn” exhibit. Participants can then design their own holiday decoration to take home. All ages.
Children gather around Saint Nick’s chair as he reads holiday classics; we’re betting the jolly guy will crack open a few books about himself and his toy-delivering adventures. All ages.
While kids work out, they teach their favorite dolls, stuffed animals and action figures how to master warrior pose. Ages 3 to 6.

Keep your brood’s brains humming on this school holiday by testing their knowledge of the Olympiad (make sure they know how many rings are in the infamous logo). Younger participants are invited to bring an older sibling to help out. Arrive promptly at 3 to secure your spot as a contestant. All ages.

At 10:30am, catch The Red Balloon. Almost completely devoid of dialogue, this 34-minute French film has been a classic since its debut in 1956. After the screening, a balloon artist will create animals for kids to take home. At 1:30pm, older kids who’ve stuck around may enjoy watching White Mane, a short film about a wild stallion and the young boy who manages to tame him. A storytelling workshop led by banjo-playing author Bill Gordh follows the flick. Ages 3 and up.

text.content: For single screening: $10, children under 14 $7; for double feature: $18, children under 14 $12

event.description: Every Saturday, this Upper West Side institution opens its doors and offers complimentary activities and healthy snacks. Weekly events include art projects, a toddler play space, a rooftop playground (weather permitting), games and more. All ages.

If your family doesn’t celebrate Christmas, that doesn’t mean you have to spend the day watching movies and chowing down on lo mein. Instead, head to the Jewish Museum for arts-and-crafts projects, live music and gallery activities. Ages 3 and up.

Following the Tribeca Cinemas Kids Club morning screenings of Lamb Chop television episodes, your kids can view Steven Spielberg’s classic alien-hidden-in-the-suburbs gem. A discussion on film critics follows the flick, and kids will get a chance to critique the film. Our only suggestion? Sneak in some Reese’s Pieces. Ages 7 and up.

text.content: For a single screening $10, children under 14 $7; for a double feature $18, children under 14 $12

event.description: Pint-sized paleontologists can celebrate all things dino at this weekend-long fest celebrating the return of “Sue,” the world’s largest, best preserved, and most complete T.Rex skeleton ever found. Kids can search for and take home real fossils, chat with a dino doc, and even get their faces painted in true Steogsaurus or Raptor fashion. All ages.

It's only been a few months since Halloween, but if your little one is itching to put that costume back on, take her to this celebration of a holiday that originated in Denmark. Kids dress in costume and collect treats for the Fastelavn feast (sound familiar?); at this gathering they can play the traditional games of the holiday and learn songs. Ages 5 and up.

If your kids know all the words to songs from movies like The Little Mermaid, Beauty and the Beast, or Aladdin (who doesn’t?), they’ll be belting them out at this concert tribute for the eight-time Academy Award winning composer. Menkin himself will make an appearance at the event, which includes sing-alongs, fun facts, games, medleys and mini-musicals. Be our guest! All ages.

If your tots are already bouncing off the walls with yuletide excitement, bring them to Staten Island for an early dose of merriment. On Friday, kids bake “stained-glass” Christmas cookies; on Saturday and Sunday they design wrapping paper, which they can take home and use to decorate presents; and on Sunday only, tots can hear a holiday-themed storytime. Ages 5 to 10.
What better way to celebrate the Lunar New Year than at a traditional tea ceremony? Flushing’s own Luh Yu Tea Emporium is the host of this aromatherapeutic extravaganza. All ages.
Head to this weekly reading of popular books for preschoolers. Jon Samson of CoCreative Music provides tunes and a music lesson. Ages 2 to 5.

While your brood is out of school this week, they can drop in and discover the museum's current exhibit on this surreal and experimental artist. Kids will craft a mobile using found objects and recycled materials, keeping the art they see in mind for inspiration. Ages 4 and up.

This family program uncovers the story of the 1887 Eldridge Street Synagogue, allowing participants to explore the history of immigrant life on the Lower East Side. Each program includes conversations and art-making activities inspired by the building’s history and architecture. Ages 5 to 10.

Presented by Livable Streets Education, a group that teaches young students how to make positive changes in their neighborhoods, this workshop focuses on ways to improve New York City streets. Children will create shoebox dioramas that represent their visions for urban living in the future. Ages 5 and up.

Tots jam with Mark Stuart and Rob Schwimmer of Polygraph Lounge, a duo that can take just about anything—a baseball bat, a bouncy ball, a water glass—and turn it into an instrument. They’ll play these makeshift music makers along with the piano, electric guitar and theremin to get little ones grooving. Ages 2 to 6.
Families can decorate a special holiday house–edible of course!–with tons of tasty treats. All ages.

Dinosaur enthusiast Richie Mirissis presents three-dimensional models and other artifacts from his large collection. Kids can also dig for real fossils in a temporary pit set up for the event and make clay models of their findings. Ages 3 to 12.

event.identifier: Sammie and Tudie’s Comedy Magic Circus
event.description: Two clowns wearing funny hats and wacky socks blend classic big-top sketches with audience participation, storytelling and magic. Ages 3 and up.
event.sort_string: Sammie and Tudie's Comedy Magic Circus

event.description: If you're looking for a way to keep your mischief-makers out of trouble during their school break, then what better place to send them than this drop-off program at the Police Museum? Each day, kids will learn all about law enforcement through different themes, including CSI, cop vehicles, communication and sketch artistry. On Friday, they'll use their newly learned skills to solve a mystery. Pre-register by calling 212-480-3100, ext 116. Ages 6 to 12.

Come celebrate Hanukkah with The Educational Alliance Preschool, where families can learn about the school's programs. Festivities include Hanukkah arts and crafts, sing-a-longs, storytelling, dreidel games, kosher refreshments and more. All ages.

“If you love bacon so much, why don’t you marry it?” You've heard that one from your youngsters before; now they can see the scenario in the Opera Group/ROH2’s production. The humorous show is based on a Romanian fairy tale about three sisters who are fated to marry a prince from the east, a prince from the west and...an oinker. The whole family will travel to the moon and back with Princess Flora, the unlucky youngest sibling who is destined to have a hog for a husband. This kooky opera is filled with ice-cream cone-inspired wigs, gobs of bubble gum, and silly songs that are bound to tickle every funny bone in the audience. Ages 7 and up.
Company XIV, a Brooklyn based theater-dance group, presents the World Premiere of their family holiday show Snow White. All ages.
Too chilly to hit the real zoo? Head to this meet-and-greet with slithery creatures and hear a reading of George Edward Stanley’s Snake Camp. Ages 3 to 8.

Leave the triple axels behind. This time, it’s all about the moonwalk…or, the moonskate. Bust a move to the tunes of Michael Jackson and pay tribute to the late legend’s greatest hits. We’re not sure how he could move that way on land, but your little dancers have a better chance of pulling it off on ice. Children attending on their birthdays receive free admission, hot chocolate and popcorn. All ages.

text.content: $5, seniors and children under 15 $3; $6.50 skate rental

event.description: Tiny tots might relate to the title character in Robot Zot!, the newest book from Jon Scieszka, creator of Trucktown and collaborator on the Caldecott-honored Stinky Cheese Man. Intent on taking control of the world, Robot Zot has just one problem: He’s only three inches tall. Kids can hear the author talk about the tale and have him ink their copies. Ages 4 to 8.

text.content: Advance tickets: $18, children under 17 $12; day of show $20, children under 17 $12

event.description: Time Out Kids fave Morgan Taylor leads a performance that features live music and appearances by the frontman’s animated alter ego—Gustafer Yellowgold, a cuddly, cone-headed creature who was born on the sun. Also look for fan favorite, Jonathan Samson of CoCreative Music as he plays original songs from Kids Album. Antsy tots can take a break from the tunes to hit up the arts and crafts provided by Artscetera. Ages 3 and up.

Families engage in craft projects inspired by discussions and activities in the galleries. In this session, kids will examine paintings, drawings and photographs themed around “cropping and composition,” in which they’ll learn how artists experiment and make decisions in their art. Ages 6 to 10.

Nobody’s secrets are safe from Sam Eaton. Bring your brood to this one-man show where they can have their minds read by the self-proclaimed mentalist. Each of Eaton’s routines requires a volunteer, so there’s a good chance your child will make his or her stage debut. Ages 8 and up.

Based on Hans Christian Andersen’s fairy tale, this production emphasizes the role children play in keeping the world a happy place. Seeing the show is an ideal way to boost your tyke’s self-image and bring a tear to a sentimental parent’s eye. All ages.

event.identifier: “Moving the Millions: New York City's Subway, from Its Origins to the Present.”
event.description: Take a trip to the past on vintage subway and elevated cars. A working signal tower heightens the verisimilitude of this rapid-transit showcase.
event.sort_string: “Moving the Millions: New York City's Subway, from Its Origins to the Present.”

event.identifier: Tales of the Milky Way Workshop
event.description: Your little space-traveler can hear Asian stories about the Milky Way, then write her own glittering galaxy tale. Ages 3 to 12.

text.content: $10 for children under 13, free for children under 1

event.sort_string: Tales of the Milky Way Workshop

event.description: Stand-up comic and magician Rich Marotta and his assistant Twila Zone (Tamara Marotta) make the funny appear out of thin air in this family-friendly stage show. All ages.

Youngsters travel over the river and through the woods with Earth Camp's Seth Wollney, as they explore how Staten Island's parks change in the winter time. On Thursday, they'll visit Clay Pit Ponds State Park Preserve; Friday expect a trip to Blue Heron Park. Pre-registration required. Call 718-483-7105 for more information and meet-up locations. Ages 8 to 13.

event.identifier: Ballet for Young Audiences presents The Nutcracker
event.description: Adapted to suit children, this hour-long version of the classic holiday season ballet is fully narrated. That means your little one is sure to latch on to Clara and her doll’s journey into a magical realm. All ages.
event.sort_string: Ballet for Young Audiences presents The Nutcracker

event.description: The wolf is almost likable, and definitely funny—he complains that Grandma tastes “tough” when he gobbles her down—in this musical telling of the fairy tale about a little girl’s chancy journey through the woods. Ages 3 and up.

event.identifier: Shakespeare to Go: A Midsummer Night's Dream
event.description: Introduce your young thespians to the Bard’s work in this kid-friendly adaptation of one of his most magical plays. Let the playful sprite Puck be your guide as you and your brood watch what happens when you mix together fairy royalty, a donkey, a traveling band of actors, two wandering couples and some misplaced love potion. A pre-show workshop (10AM) and a post-show talk back offer multiple opportunities to chat and learn about the famous playwright and the show. Ages 8 and up.
event.sort_string: Shakespeare to Go: A Midsummer Night's Dream

event.description: “This is the song that never ends; yes, it goes on and on, my friends.” We’re sure you’ve heard that one before, even though ventriloquist Shari Lewis’s beloved sock puppet Lamb Chop no longer makes regular television appearances. Today, kids can catch back-to-back episodes of The Shari Lewis Show and Lamb Chop’s Play-Along on the big screen. A puppeteer will give a lesson on ventriloquism following the show. If your family is up for a double feature, stick around to watch E.T.; it plays at 1:30pm. Ages 3 and up.

text.content: For a single screening: $10, children under 14 $7; for a double-feature: $18, children under 14 $12

event.description: Double your fun at this crafty class, where you and your tykes can make not one, but two different projects. Your little one's options include creating a colorful mosaic out of little stones or rendering a miniature NYC street. Ages 5 to 12.

It’s a holiday miracle—sit your kid on the jolly guy’s lap without doling out big bucks for the photo op. Bring your own camera to snap the shot, and head to Pier 17’s third-floor atrium for a gratis visit with the man in red. All ages.

Alongside Scooter, Dr. Nebula’s trusty assistant, young scientists will engage in hands-on activities that reveal the properties of cold and how temperature affects different types of matter. Ages 4 to 10.

Cold weather wearing you down? Take a mental vacation South of the Border at this Mexican holiday happening. Kids can watch a pastorela (a short biblical play about the shepherds of Christmas fame), beat open a piñata and nosh on tasty regional treats. Ages 4 and up.

The aerial nouveau-cirque troupe Suspended Circus dangles over your head like human mistletoe in this acrobatic revue, which includes ice maidens on trapeze and Santa riding a unicycle. This kid-friendly matinee is less risque than the troupe's normal show. Ages 7 and up.

Kiddos can decorate a holiday gingerbread house with the help of The Peninsula’s culinary team. The class also includes hot cocoa, finger sandwiches and sweets. While children are hard at work, parents can enjoy their own tea, complete with gourmet tea sandwiches, a selection of teas, scones and pastries. During the second hour of the class, Mrs. Claus will read a holiday story aloud and snap shots with tots. Reservations required. Ages 7 and up.

event.identifier: The Tortoise & the Hare’s Holiday Hoop-La
event.description: Denise Devin and Christopher Reiner’s family musical warbles its message about friendship, teamwork and holiday spirit through a cast of “animal friends, snowflakes, dancing matzo balls and hum-bugs.” Ages 3 and up.

event.identifier: The Nutcracker Sweets and The Steadfast Tin Soldier
event.description: Two tales are presented at this performance: First up is a marionette adaptation of the delectable “Land of Sweets” scene from Tchaikovsky’s Nutcracker. Then different puppets enact the bittersweet Hans Christian Andersen story of a doomed romance between two toys: a tin soldier and a paper doll. All ages.
event.sort_string: Nutcracker Sweets and The Steadfast Tin Soldier

event.description: Get ready for a feast for the senses—this classic ballet features Tchaikovsky’s majestic score, opulent sets and costumes, and a cast of fantastical characters. Princess-loving little ones will fall head over heels for the familiar fairy tale, featuring a beautiful royal who slumbers endlessly thanks to a witch’s curse. But don’t worry: As in the Disney movie, she’s saved by a handsome prince. Ages 5 and up.

Calling all chocoholic children! Chef Keith Williams of the Crowne Plaza Hotel’s Brasserie 1605 is channeling Willy Wonka by inviting city kids to learn the art of making chocolate. With Williams’s help, youngsters will create edible treats including truffles, fudge, caramels and chocolate-covered strawberries. Candy-enthusiast parents can either sit in on the lessons or indulge in a treat of their own: a drink at the hotel bar. Golden ticket not required. Ages 6 to 12.

Boo and Elena from the Demolition String Band give folk and country classics new acoustic life. Kids can practice hoedown steps to the accompaniment of guitars, fiddles, mandolins and banjos playing hits by Hank Williams, Loretta Lynn, the Carter Family and Johnny Cash. Ages 6 months to 10 years.

Kids get in on the recent Julie & Julia–inspired cooking craze by learning to bake French delicacies. Instructor Sylvie Berger, who worked as a pastry assistant at La Grande Épicerie, incorporates the French language into the class as she teaches youngsters to craft pain d’épices, or spice bread. Ages 5 to 11.

Gowanus Music Club presents a rock concert featuring six GMC kids bands and one GMC adult band from the fall semester. Expect a variety of musical genres and plenty of opportunities to get up and dance. Ages 7 and up.
Combining guitar, sax, bass and percussion with songs in a variety of foreign languages (plus English), Hot Peas ’N Butter brings multiculturalism to the young masses. All ages.
Costumed characters and colonial music enliven a presentation about Hamilton’s influence on the formation of present-day democracy. Ages 7 and up.

Introduce the little ones to Atka, an Arctic gray wolf from the Wolf Conservation Center in South Salem, New York. Youngsters will learn about his species’ vital role in maintaining our planet’s ecosystem. Ages 3 and up.

Tiny tea drinkers can enjoy kiddie fare in an upper-crust setting thanks to father-of-three and chef Marc Taxiera’s menu. PB&J blini and little-pigs-in-blankets are some of the offerings for kids; the spot’s delectable petits fours and smoked salmon are top choices among adults. Ages 2 to 12.

Children gear up for good dreams and focus on inner peace at this evening class. Because they’ll be engaged in restful poses so close to bedtime, students are encouraged to come in their sleepwear. At the end of the program, milk and cookies serve as a sweet send-off. Call for reservations. Ages 4 to 6.

event.identifier: Junior Science Club: Our Unique Selves, from Fingerprints to Taste
event.description: In this biology-focused workshop, your kids will learn about the phenomenal physical and sensory traits that make each human unique. Ages 8 to 13.
event.sort_string: Junior Science Club: Our Unique Selves, from Fingerprints to Taste

event.identifier: Tech for Tots: Learning with Digital Cameras
event.description: Bring your budding photographer to this interactive workshop where he can learn basic skills and improve his snapshots. Reservations suggested. Ages 2 to 6.
event.sort_string: Tech for Tots: Learning with Digital Cameras

event.identifier: NYC Lab School Winter Holiday Concert
event.description: While you sip on hot cocoa and nosh on gingerbread by Craft Sweets ($3), students of the NYC Lab School’s High School Chorus will serenade you with holiday carols. All ages.
event.sort_string: NYC Lab School Winter Holiday Concert

event.description: Broadway-belting babes will likely flip to attend this workshop taught by Chelsea Krombach, the Elphaba understudy in the smash-hit musical. Students will work it out in scenes, songs and a dance combo; by the end of the four-hour class, they'll surely be “Defying Gravity.” Ages 7 to 16.

Kick off the Year of the Tiger with this day-long festival. In the morning, crafts reign supreme, and youngsters (as well as their parents) can experiment with Korean calligraphy, make Chinese paper flowers, and explore other arts from the Far East. At 1PM, listen to tunes featuring Chinese string instruements like the erhu and pipa. Cap off the day with a colorful performance of Pan-Asian folk dances at 2PM. All ages.

This weekend activity gives youngsters a tour of MoMA’s permanent collections and temporary exhibits. Little ones are encouraged to voice their opinions about what they dig (Mom and Dad can, too). Tickets will be distributed on the day of the program, beginning at 10am, at the Information Desk in the museum’s main lobby. Ages 5 to 10.

Barbara Wiechmann’s first play for children is set a century ago in the Hudson River Valley. The show’s protagonist is someone with whom your tween may relate: an 11-year-old named Annabelle who creates ghost stories for her great-aunt. Ages 9 and up.

Almost two dozen hits from ’70s pop sensation Abba form the core of this worldwide smash, which book writer Catherine Johnson has fleshed out into a mother-daughter comedy-drama. As theater, Mamma Mia! is forgettable, but fun-loving audiences can’t get enough of it. Ages 8 and up.

event.identifier: The Spirit of Kwanzaa: Obo Addy’s Okropong
event.description: Explore the sounds of Kwanzaa with West African master drummer Obo Addy; he and his percussionist gang are performing in conjunction with the center’s Children’s Festival, which includes dance workshops, face painting, drumming classes, storytelling and a book fair. All activities focus on the spirit of Kwanzaa. Ages 10 and up.
event.sort_string: Spirit of Kwanzaa: Obo Addy’s Okropong
