event.description: Join NYC-based author Hill for a reading and signing of her recent children’s book, Urban Animals, which depicts carvings and sculptures of critters on building facades throughout the Big Apple. Attendees will also have the chance draw and sculpt animals with clay. Ages 5 and up.

Andrew Lloyd Webber’s musical of Gaston Leroux’s 1911 novel, set in 19th-century Paris, is a lavish, melodramatic and spooky operetta that plays well enough to garner standing ovations and resounding applause many years into its run. Proof that it must be doing something right, Phantom is the longest-running show in Broadway history. Ages 10 and up.

Project Runway addicts will love this workshop in which kids “make it work,” as Tim Gunn might say, while they custom-design T-shirts, bags and accessories. Products by the interactive agency R/GA (the brains behind the Nike Plus ad campaign) provide inspiration as children get their creative juices flowing. Be sure to stop by the Cooper-Hewitt’s “Design USA: Contemporary Innovation” exhibit, where more of R/GA’s work is on display. Preregister by calling 212-849-8353. Ages 5 to 13.

If you’ve got youngsters who can’t get enough of things that glimmer and gleam, take them to this workshop, where they’ll fashion shiny foil, glittery beads and natural adornments into gifts and decorations with help from Colombian-American artist Esperanza Cortés. All ages.

For the first time since Dick Van Dyke and Chita Rivera fronted the 1961 version, Bye Bye Birdie returns to the Main Stem. The young performers are unquestionably the heart and soul of this candy-colored production, and the presentation of celeb worship is still spot on; JoBro-loving tweens will certainly identify with Kim MacAfee’s overblown crush on hip-swiveling musician Conrad Birdie. The teenagers also don’t disappoint in the crowd favorite, “The Telephone Hour,” in which they excitedly gab to one another from phone booths. While other bouncy pop-rock tunes like “A Lot of Livin’ to Do” might be too sugary for jaded adults, they’ll likely inspire hook-happy youngsters to download the soundtrack. Unfortunately, the musical’s most recognizable ditty, “Put On a Happy Face,” falls flat, right along with John Stamos’s lifeless performance as the teen superstar’s pushy agent, Albert. Ages 6 and up.

Outdoor caroling isn’t always possible in winter weather, so enjoy this chance to hear your favorite holiday ditties sung indoors at the Morgan. Introduce your kids to this holiday tradition as you listen to a mix of traditional tunes and popular music performed all throughout the museum by singers from Mannes College The New School for Music. All ages.

event.identifier: Listen to the Wind Paper Doll Portraits
event.description: After viewing an exhibition of collage-illustrations by Susan Roth, inspired youngsters use assorted patterns and materials to create paper dolls with similar qualities. Ages 5 and up.
event.sort_string: Listen to the Wind Paperdoll Portraits

event.description: Listen to “Deck the Halls” at the docks, as this group of barbershop doo-woppers harmonize holiday carols. All ages.

event.identifier: The Little Orchestra Society Presents “The Orchestra—A Happy Family”
event.description: Your little maestro can learn about all the components of an orchestra, in this colorful performance. Distracting that sweet tooth with a magical world filled with candy canes, chocolates and musical treats, tots are introduced to drums, strings, brass and winds. Ages 3 to 5.
event.sort_string: Little Orchestra Society Presents “The Orchestra—A Happy Family”

event.description: The Brooklyn-based artist’s works range from geometric shapes and lines to monochromatic scenes of car crashes. Your tots can see some of his original paintings and drawings up close, and then create their own inspired artworks. Ages 5 and up.

Although the setting of the The Lion King was slightly balmier than an ice skating rink, the Disney classics blasting overhead during this themed skate time will certainly get your little ones moving on the ice. And if not, well, there’s always hot chocolate. All ages.

Sip eggnog and hot apple cider while touring the rooms of the museum (by candlelight!), which will be kitted out for the holidays in historically appropriate Christmas trimmings. Holiday tunes will be played on traditional instruments like the fiddle and violin. All ages.

event.identifier: Sesame Street Celebrates Around the World
event.description: Follow anchorman Elmo and the Monster News Network as they report how people across the globe welcome the New Year. Ages 2 to 6.
event.sort_string: Sesame Street Screening: Celebrates Around the World

event.description: This Ballet for Young Audiences production of the classic Tchaikovsky masterpiece features music, dance and, as a bonus, talking! Thanks to the clear format, even the littlest kids will be able to follow the Nutcracker Prince on his adventure through the Forbidden Forest and the Kingdom of Sweets. All ages.

text.content: $15, students and children ages 4-12 $12, children under 4 free

event.description: Browse the homemade goods from local tween artists including decorations, crafts, jewelry and more. All ages.
Under Louis Mofsie’s direction, the Thunderbird Indian Dancers and Singers perform traditional social dances to the drumming of Heyna Second Sons. All ages.
Visitors uncover what humans have in common with plants, bacteria and marine mammals.

Let tots play with an interactive board to learn about foods that are healthy and snacks that aren't so good for their growing bodies. Then, kids will make silhouettes of themselves and craft a collage or draw pictures of what they can’t wait to put into their rumbling tummies. Ages 5 to 12.
Children can dress in costume, try on stage makeup and play with theater props. Bright theatrical lighting and a real sound board help kids imagine what it’s like to put on a show.

event.identifier: The New York Pops present The Polar Express
event.description: THIS CONCERT IS SOLD OUT. If you thought reading The Polar Express couldn’t be any more fun than it already is, think again. The New York Pops orchestra presents a musical version of Chris Van Allsburg’s classic holiday tale as part of Carnegie Hall’s Family Concert series. John Tartaglia of Avenue Q narrates, and the Young People’s Chorus of New York City accompanies the orchestra. Arrive an hour before the show for gratis activities (for ticket holders only). Ages 5 to 12.

Take your infant on an outing to this gratis sampling of the venue’s weekly sign language course. Based on American Sign Language vocabulary, the program is intended to help babes communicate with their parents as they’re learning to speak. Call to reserve a space. Ages 3 months and up.

Join BAX’s regular MC, Jumpin’ Juniper, the 100-year-old tree-sprite alter ego of actress Joanna Walchuk, as she hosts “The Wizard of Iz,” a mix of video projections and a live performance from choreographer Charles Dennis. Kids will see clips from several films, including the Wizard of Oz and Jurassic Park, while Dennis enacts various characters. After the visual feast, kids can hang out in a staffed, indoor play space full of toys. Ages 2 and up.

text.content: $15 per adult/child pair, $8 each additional person

event.description: Got rhythm crazed youngsters whose devotion to the drums would rival Animal of The Muppet Show? Take them to this concert, where they’ll get to explore different beats and instruments from all over the globe. Ages 3 to 12.

With the help of French artist and bookmaker Nathalie Trovato, pint-sized publishers will learn how to bind books using recycled materials. Don't forget to round up scrap paper, colorful plastic bags with text and patterns, and other pieces that your tot can transform into a one-of-a-kind livre. Ages 7 to 10.

Tykes celebrate the Jewish festival of lights as they watch this seasonal episode. Actor Jeremy Miller explores the land of the Maccabees, while Levana White hosts Dreidel of Fortune (heh). Moishe Oofnik avoids stings while baking jellyfish doughnuts. Ages 2 to 6.
event.sort_string: Sesame Street Screening: Shalom Sesame Chanukah

event.description: Jazz is a quintessentially New York art form, which means that taking in a concert is a veritable rite of passage. With an eye (or rather, ear) toward educating young people about the genre early on, the Blue Smoke Jazz Standard holds a weekly program aimed at school-age kids. The Jazz Standard Youth Orchestra, a group of talented instrumentalists, provides the music. Doors open at 1pm. All ages.

text.content: $5 donation will benefit the Jazz Standard Discovery Program for kids

event.description: This hot NYC-based children’s band helps you and your brood celebrate Purim by playing original upbeat, kid-approved tunes. Tots enjoy klezmer rock while dancing in costume to “ClownaHagila” and much more. Ages 3 and up.

Kids gain an appreciation for diversity from a screening of the award-winning film The Peach Tree, from director Mitra Sen. The story finds young Shazia, a Muslim who celebrates Eid, and her friend Kylie, a Christian who observes Christmas, struggling to enlighten their parents about each other’s traditions. After the show, kids enjoy an arts-and-crafts activity in which they’ll get to work together to build a faux peach tree. All ages.

This classic French film from 1956 is just 34 minutes long, and follows the adventures of a young boy and a red balloon as the two wander through the streets of Paris. After the screening, children will make their own poetic (“Roses are red…”) floating valentines. All ages.

In this hands-on activity, kids trace their outlines on a life-size sheet of paper and depict their thoughts and dreams in the surrounding empty space. And don’t only expect images of Nintendo Wii and chocolate cupcakes—a Jain painting inspires the exercise, so you can expect an art history lesson or two within Sarah’s Chocolate Chip Universe. All ages.

event.identifier: “The Butterfly Conservatory: Tropical Butterflies Alive in Winter”
event.description: Temperatures climb to a balmy 80 degrees in the 1,315-square-foot vivarium, returning for its 12th year. Kids can see many species of the flying creatures in a spectrum of shapes, sizes and colors. All ages.

Every week, LIC Kids offers a menu of classes that will work out your kid's brain and brawn. Programs include gymnastics, martial arts, dance, yoga, as well as chess, music, movement-based theatre and after-school tutoring programs. The gym is also accessible for daily open play sessions. A hair cutting station for kids is also available.

This former Chinese ringmaster turned children's author brings your tot's imaginative fantasies to life during this storytelling performance that features her latest, Jin Jin and Rain Wizard. Kids can watch and listen as the author acts out the dragon tale through puppetry, magical illusions and mime. Ages 3 and up.
Just in time for the New Year, you and your brood can paint a Wave Hill–inspired calendar to mark off the days of 2010. All ages.

Israel’s only classical and neoclassical ballet company, which is comprised of 35 dancers, hits the Brooklyn stage with all the machismo that this show, based on Cervantes’ classical Spanish novel, has to offer. Set against a vibrant video enhanced backdrop, the love-struck knight and his trailing squire plié and pirouette after the saucy senorita Dulcinea. Ages 8 and up.

This Tony Award–nominated stage production is based on the 1954 Bing Crosby–Danny Kaye flick. Just like in the classic film, the musical centers on two showbiz veterans who meet their love matches while putting on a show in a Vermont inn. White Christmas boasts music and lyrics by the legendary Irving Berlin, and direction by Walter Bobbie, the man who brought the popular Chicago revival to Broadway. All ages.

Curators, arts educators and artists give kiddos lessons in various techniques, such as collage, printmaking, stencil making, sculpture, photography and more. Mention Time Out Kids when signing up to get a 15% discount. Portions of the proceeds will benefit Public Art for Public Schools. Ages 5 to 12.

Just because they live in the city doesn’t mean your kids wouldn’t relish a country Christmas. Today, children can tour a seasonally decorated farmhouse, sip warm cider and craft a holiday-themed masterpiece at an activity station. All ages.

The kiddie crooner performs a concert, highlighting tunes from his new album 76 Trombones. In addition to hearing the popular performer live, kids will see special appearances by tap dancer Derick K. Grant and other artists from Brooklyn. All ages.

event.identifier: Wilderness & Wildlife in New York City
event.description: Let naturalist and educator Gabriel Willow of New York City Audubon show your family the wilder side of our concrete jungle. Along with a tour of the photography exhibition, “Legacy: The Preservation of Wildnerness in New York City Parks,” kids will learn about the animals that inhabit the city's green spaces. Then, your brood will create their own urban habitat. Ages 5 to 10.
event.sort_string: Wilderness & Wildlife in New York City

event.description: Families celebrate the holiday that marks the beginning of the harvest season in India and all of Southeast Asia by engaging in crafty activities, like creating miniature kites or making sugar candy garlands. Ages 3 to 12.

text.content: $10 for children under 13, free for children under 1

event.description: The musical duo performs upbeat songs about flying fish and confused dogs who think they’re frogs. Make sure your kids are raring to dance to punk music and croon along to bluegrass tunes. Listen up for a few new songs from the bands January album release, Rise and Shine. All ages.

text.content: Advance tickets $18, children under 12 $12; at the door $19, children under 12 $13

event.description: As they learn about ways to protect the earth’s underwater ecosystem, children get to handle live sea creatures. All ages.

event.identifier: Galli's Wolf and the 7 Little Goats
event.description: Kids can watch their peers perform in this all-children-cast play. In humorous production, the youngsters play goats who can't tell if their visitor is their mother or a hungry wolf. Ages 3 and up.
event.sort_string: Galli's Wolf and the 7 Little Goats

event.description: Celebrate Purim by diving into an afternoon of activites. Kids can experience what it’s like to immigrate to America, or try their hand at grinding wheat and hunting for food with a bow and arrow in the Galleries’ two interactive exhibits, “From Home to Home: Jewish Immigration in America” and “From Tent to Temple: Life In the Ancient Near East.” Then, tots can join in on a hunt for treasure. Wrap up the day with some arts and crafts as you help your brood create Purim-centric costumes, noisemakers and puppets. Ages 5 to 12.

event.identifier: Brady Rymer and the Little Band that Could
event.description: A Grammy-nominated musician (and dad), Rymer mixes rock & roll, folk, pop and blues in happy-go-lucky tunes that entice kids to get up and dance. Ages 4 and up.
event.sort_string: Brady Rymer and the Little Band that Could

event.description: Fidgety hands are put to good use constructing tambourines. After the activity, the Percussion People (whose members include tween-age musician Emily Sgouros) drum up harmony using a wide range of instruments, from triangles and bongos to several not-so-standard melody makers. Be prepared to endure some serious noise. All ages.

event.identifier: 4 Wings, 2 Legs, Ukeleles and a Tale
event.description: At this two-day showcase, bands (including the Ukeladies and punk-rock outfit Dirty Power: Weena Pauly, Katy Pyle and Katie Workum) will provide dancing tunes; performance artist YaliniDream will blend storytelling, song and dance into an act incorporating her pet monkey; and neo-vaudevillian clown El Macho del Norte (embodied by John Leo) will let loose during a set of giggle-inducing physical comedy and melodies. All ages.
event.sort_string: 4 Wings, 2 Legs, Ukeleles and a Tale

event.description: Children under six can hang out in hands-on activity nooks like a multiethnic market, a construction area and a sensory zone for babies.
This maritime museum is your young one’s oyster during afternoon playtime, where tots engage with history, science, and seaworthy activities and storytimes. Ages 6 months to 4 years.

event.identifier: John Carlin & the Kids Music Underground Concert
event.description: Carlin & Co. present kid-oriented rock music, including their hit songs “One Family” and “A Dinosaur Named Fred.” Frontman John Carlin has genuine indie cred—his former band toured with P.J. Harvey and Radiohead back in the day. Ages 2 to 10.
event.sort_string: John Carlin & The Kids Music Underground Concert

event.description: This candy-colored celebration of teen lust and ’60s kitsch (originally sired by shockmaster John Waters) has plenty of hormones and heart, plus a supercatchy score. Back in New York on its national tour, the show follows a chubby teen as she boogies her way onto an American Bandstand–esque dance show and steals the series’ hunk from a blond bully. Ages 8 and up.

text.content: $30-$40, half price tickets for children under 19

event.description: Leave behind the hipster streets of the modern Lower East Side when you step back in time and meet the immigrants who made the nabe into the vibrant, multicultural spot it is today. In this new tour, costumed storytellers reenact the lives of actual former residents of 97 Orchard Street, playing everyone from a Depression-era Italian family to a Sephardic Jewish teenage girl from 1916. Young historians will have the chance to create a tenement-themed craft to take home. Ages 5 and up.

The celebrations in honor of 40 years of the Street continues! Families can participate in arts and crafts, hear bilingual stories read aloud, watch “The Adventures of Elmo in Grounchland” and other fun activities. All ages.

Children can explore a two-story child-sized home and learn how to tile its bathroom, shingle its roof, lay pipes, fix wires and decorate. Kids can even cut their own wood for the projects (with a bit of museum-provided supervision, of course). The exhibit also addresses construction on a broader scale, challenging youngsters to configure Staten Island’s buildings in new ways.

Fronted by a former elementary school teacher and a published kid’s novelist, this Seattle-based group brings you and your tots jangly power pop akin to The Shins and the Posies. Their high-energy tunes touch on everything from global warming to the perils of being a lonely tomato. All ages.
Each week, this popular 90-minute program invites kids to explore the galleries and make their own art. Meet promptly at 11am or 2pm in the Rubin Lobby every Saturday and Sunday. Ages 4 to 7.

text.content: $10 materials fee per family of four plus museum admission

event.description: Head to the new Clinton Hill bookstore for a story time reading from local parent and novelist Touré, who will read How the Grinch Stole Christmas and other holiday books. All ages.

Based on novelist Gregory Maguire’s 1995 adult variation on L. Frank Baum’s Oz mythology, Wicked provides a prequel to the children’s book and movie. The musical addresses complex themes, such as standards of beauty, morality and, believe it or not, opposition to fascism. Thanks to a witty book by Winnie Holzman (creator of ’90s cult angstfest My So-Called Life) and composer-lyricist Stephen Schwartz’s robust score, Wicked soars. Ages 8 and up.

Get ready to groove as you take in Meredith Wright’s soulful, energetic tunes for kids. Her sweet and funky jams celebrate the joys of being a little kid in the big city, touching on everything from neighborhoods to hairdos. Ages 4 to 12.

Whitney teaching fellows lead tours of the exhibition “Georgia O’Keeffe: Abstraction” for new moms and dads and their tiny tots when the museum is otherwise closed to the public. For once, crying babies are welcome! Ages newborn to 18 months.

event.identifier: The Goldfish Twins Swim the Big Blue Sea
event.description: This musical comedy from the Limecat Family Theatre Company follows two goldfish who find themselves in a maritime adventure with dancing crabs, magic eels, singing turtles and other colorful creatures. All ages.
event.sort_string: Goldfish Twins Swim the Big Blue Sea

event.description: Kids can sing and dance their way through a multi-cultural journey of Africa, America, and the Caribbean with storyteller Tammy Hall, a Tennessee native who began spinning tales at Brooklyn's own Lefferts Historic House Museum in 1996. Ages 4 to 12.

event.identifier: Seven in One Blow, or The Brave Little Kid
event.description: Randy Sharp directs a company-devised adaptation of the fairy tale in which a boy gets an unfairly fearsome reputation after swatting flies. An onscreen guest appearance by Deborah Harry may help with the buzz factor. Ages 4 and up.
Celebrate the winter holiday trifecta (Christmas, Hanukkah and Kwanzaa) with musical educator Miranda at this interactive show. All ages.

Three deadpan, blue-skinned men with extraterrestrial imaginations carry this tourist fave, a show as smart as it is ridiculous. They drum on open tubs of paint, creating splashes of color; they consume Twinkies and Cap’n Crunch; they engulf the audience in a roiling sea of toilet paper. For sheer weird, exuberant fun, it’s hard to top this long-running treat. Ages 5 and up.

The gifted musical-theater composer Peter Mills unwraps a family musical about a little girl in a post-evergreen world who goes on a quest to find the last examples of the pine kind. Cara Reichel directs. All ages.

event.identifier: New York City National Comedy Theatre Show
event.description: Two teams of professional comics compete against each other based solely on audience suggestions. Ages 10 and up.
event.sort_string: New York City National Comedy Theatre Show

event.description: Harry Potter costumes aren’t the only thing you can find at this Halloween emporium: A free magic show catering to kids casts its spell every Sunday afternoon. Dumbledore doesn’t make an appearance, but the store’s magician performs a pretty cool disappearing trick. All ages.

Abounding with New Orleans jazz tunes, this show follows a Creole flatboat captain named Annie who pulls a boatload of toys through a frightening storm on Christmas Eve—saving the holiday for lots of kids. Enacted by puppets, the production opens with an energetic sing-along of tunes honoring Christmas, Chanukah, Kwanzaa, and Three Kings day. All ages.

Zina Goldrich and Marcy Heisler, the songwriting duo behind the popular Junie B. Jones musical, bring back this Time Out Kids–approved show. The title character is the fancifully named Edwina Spoonapple, a young lady who thrives on doling out advice about being polite at birthday parties and dealing with pesky siblings. Your brood will likely be humming the show’s quirky (and infectious) songs like “Hola Lola” and “Frankenguest” for days. As a special bonus, Goldrich and Heisler will take the stage after Friday night performances in January to chat with the audience and perform some of their songs. Ages 5 to 12.

Families have been attending this annual winter concert for 30 years. Children will hear carols and other traditional tunes performed by the Young People’s Chorus of New York City, the Cathedral of St. Patrick Choir, Schola Cantorum on Hudson and the Cathedral organs. All ages.

Erin Lee & Marci, the self-proclaimed “Indigo Girls meets the Smothers Brothers” duo, will get your tots rockin’ to hilarious yet hip songs about loose teeth, terrible haircuts and other kiddie conundrums. Ages 2 to 8.
Storyteller Regina Ress presents tales and songs from Sweden. Ages 5 and up.

Your brood can connect, work together and ring in the new decade in a Zen way by making a tree of life, complete with paper cutouts and sculptures that symbolize your youngsters’ hopes and dreams for 2010. Ages 3 to 12.

text.content: $10 for children under 13, free for kids under 1

event.description: A tot obsessed with eating pink cupcakes finds herself turning her favorite rosy hue (which still beats the stuffing out of getting fat) in this musical with book and lyrics by Elizabeth and Victoria Kann and music by John Gregor. Teresa K. Pond directs. All ages.

On the third Saturday of the month, El Museo opens its doors to anyone who wants to explore Latino Culture—for free. Families can expect concerts, exhibitions, gallery tours, art making workshops, film screenings and more. All ages.

The desire for lush flowers and trees within a concrete jungle should seem familiar to your little city slicker. Join Liam on a quest to greenify his city in Peter Brown’s newest children’s book, The Curious Garden. Inspired by our very own High Line, Brown talks of his writing process, and the very city that sparked the idea for this tale. Ages 3 and up.

At this workshop hosted by Private Picassos, older kids (6-8) can create a styrofoam printing plate to use to create holiday cards at 11am, while younger tots (5-7) can make their own wrapping paper using rubbings of textured collagraph printing plates at 1pm. Ages 5 to 7.

Inspired by the silly operatic tale The Enchanted Pig (coming to the New Victory Theater in February), this workshop encourages kids to explore the harmonious world of opera through music (duh), movement and some hands-on art projects provided by HiArt! Ages 5 and up.

This Muppet musical take on the Dickens classic stars Michael Caine as the iconic Ebenezer Scrooge. Kermit the Frog, Gonzo the Great, Miss Piggy and their friends round out the cast of the 1992 film. All ages.

event.identifier: Stitching Stories of the Underground Railroad
event.description: At this workshop, children will examine various quilt patterns used in the era of slavery in the United States and the Underground Railroad. With the help of Joan Hodges, a fiber and craft artist, they'll find hidden messages in the fabrics. All ages.
event.sort_string: Stitching Stories of the Underground Railroad

event.identifier: Skoppa and Skrítla at the Movies
event.description: Though you may not have heard of these Icelandic pop culture figures, Skoppa and Skrítla are a children's duo who have had popularity on T.V. and the stage in their home country. Shot mostly in Iceland and Florida, this hour-long film follows the kooky characters on one of their adventures. Ages 2 and up.
event.sort_string: Skoppa and Skrítla at the Movies

event.description: Erin Lee & Marci, the self-proclaimed “Indigo Girls meets the Smothers Brothers” duo, will get your tots rockin' to hilarious-yet-hip songs about loose teeth, terrible haircuts and other kiddie conundrums. Ages 2 to 8.

Mainspring Collective and The Brooklyn Lyceum present the first installment of their new children's theater series, Monster Literature. The premiere offers a new twist on an old classic when an evil wizard threatens to destroy the holiday spirit by changing the holiday poem. Young heroine Benjy Bleeglehorn must battle an army of monsters to restore the spirit of the season. All ages.

event.identifier: Traditional Korean Music and Dance: Noreum Machi
event.description: The South Korean music and dance ensemble wows tots with elaborate costumes, traditional movements and a percussive style known as samulnori, which originated as a folk custom in rice-farming villages. The audience can take part in a preshow arts activity (at 1pm; $4, $2 for children ages 4–12), and meet the performers after the curtain. Ages 6 and up.
event.sort_string: Traditional Korean Music and Dance: Noreum Machi

event.description: After learning about the history of stained-glass windows, children will roll up their sleeves to create miniature replicas of ornamental casements. Ages 5 to 12.

text.content: The suggested donation is $5 per child

event.sort_string: Form and Function: Stained Glass Windows

event.description: This monthly afternoon dance party features the stylings of some of the city’s hippest DJs. Face painting and goodies available for purchase from a temporary outpost of kiddie boutique MadisonParker Clothing add to the fun. Ages 6 months to 7 years.
The Grammy Award–winning bassist from Johannesburg blends traditional South African folk music with contemporary jazz and salsa to invoke the holiday spirit. All ages.

text.content: $15, students and children ages 4-12 $12, children under 4 free

event.description: The New York International Children’s Film Festival presents three winter-themed animated shorts, including Canada’s Leon in Wintertime, an adventure story about a kidnapped princess and her adopted bear; Sweden’s Spot and Splodge in Snowstorm, in which the title characters become lost in a blizzard; and Russia’s Choo-Cha, the story of a mildly mischievous little boy who tries to entertain himself at a grown-up holiday party. Ages 4 and up.
This rendition of the underwater tale follows Hans Christian Andersen’s darker plot rather than Disney’s happy romance. But the production still brims with original songs and dances. Ages 3 and up.
Bluegrass for kids may seem like a wacky notion, but this ensemble’s authentic sound—with a sprinkle of Shel Silverstein and a dash of Emmylou Harris—will make a believer of you. All ages.

text.content: Advance tickets $18, children under 12 $12; at the door $19, children under 12 $13

event.description: Treat your brood to the enchantment of ancient Chinese performance art at this stunning exhibition of gymnasts, jugglers, cyclists and tumblers, whose feats of athleticism date back 2000 years. All ages.

Kids learn about cocoa treats from the 18th century, and watch as food historian, Susan McLellan Plaisted, uses tools and techniques that date back 2000 years to make some sweet treats. Ages 8 and up.

event.identifier: Stories and Painting with Debi Derryberry
event.description: Author Debi Derryberry reads her children’s book “Baby Banana” and gets kids singing along. Tots will also paint a personalized Baby Banana dinner plate, snag an autographed CD and have a photo op with the author herself. All ages.
event.sort_string: Stories and Painting with Debi Derryberry

event.description: This family-friendly band performs tracks from their first CD, “Kids Album” as well as yet-to-be-released songs from “Another Kids Album”, coming out in March 2010. All ages.

event.identifier: Fantastical Creatures: A Children’s Animal Workshop
event.description: Lions and tigers and...unicorns, oh my? Your young wildlife expert of beasts both real and mythological can explore the role of animals in their lives during this two-hour workshop. Participants will also put their opposable thumbs (take that, fire-breathing dragon!) to use, making animals out of clay, creating masks or whipping together a cool sock puppet. Ages 4 and up..
event.sort_string: Fantastical Creatures: A Children’s Animal Workshop

event.identifier: A Season of Lights: A Winter Solstice Celebration
event.description: In this workshop, kids learn about the uses and importance of light in festivals throughout the world. Your youngster will hear a reading of Nancy Luenn’s Celebrations of Light, which features 12 light-centric celebrations, then craft paper lanterns and beeswax candles. Ages 4 and up.
event.sort_string: Season of Lights: A Winter Solstice Celebration

event.identifier: Camels and Kings Workshop: A Celebration of Gift Giving
event.description: Even if your family doesn’t celebrate Christmas, your tots may enjoy hearing about the three wise men’s journey to visit the newborn Jesus. After listening to the tale, children will get to make gift boxes, costumes and sparkling crowns fit for a king or queen. Ages 4 and up.
event.sort_string: Camels and Kings Workshop: A Celebration of Gift Giving

event.description: Staff from the beloved book nook read from their favorite spring-themed stories for kids. Tots will savor hunkering down in the cozy children’s department for an hour of old-fashioned tale-telling. All ages.

You remember life before Guitar Hero and Terminator 1, 2 and 3, and according to your kids, that makes you ancient history. But you can set the record straight at this class, where you and your brood will give needlepoint and good old quill-and-ink writing a try. Your tots might not believe it at first, but you’ll be learning something new right along with them. Because, really, you’re not that old. Ages 6 to 10.

Introduce your budding environmentalists to The Discovery Channel’s award-winning series “Planet Earth,” which is full of breathtaking shots of stunning natural wonders and rare footage of elusive animals like snow leopards and exotic birds of paradise. Ages 5 and up.
As part of its ongoing “Films for Tweens” series, the museum presents Tim Burton’s spooky suburban romance starring Johnny Depp and Winona Ryder. Ages 11 to 14.

Older kiddos will enjoy this flick, which tells the tale of a man who goes on a search through Rome to find his stolen bike. The re-launch of the film is in celebration of the Vittorio de Sico film’s 60th anniversary. Ages 8 and up.

Take your ballerinas on a footloose trip through Asian cultures as the NY Institute of Culture and the Arts presents a platter of dance performances from Korea, China, Taiwan, Thailand, Malaysia and Indonesia. All ages.

Join the creator of Artkids, a program that offers kid-friendly museum tours, as she leads tots through the Met’s exhibit “American Stories: Paintings of Everyday Life, 1765–1915.” After the session, everyone will get to view the museum’s holiday tree and children will create their own drawings to take home. Ages 3 to 12.

text.content: Ages 3-7 $55, includes museum admission for child and parent; ages 8-12 $45, includes admission for child only

event.identifier: National Dance Institute Presents Imagine: A Celebration of John Lennon
event.description: Throughout last school year, thousands of young dancers enrolled at NDI learned about John Lennon’s life, art and music. The lessons culminated in May and June 2009, when the kids danced to the late Beatle’s songs in more than 70 shows across the city. At this special encore and benefit for NDI, you can see the troupe perform songs including, “Help!,” “Come Together” and, of course, “Imagine.” Ages 4 and up.
event.sort_string: National Dance Institute Presents Imagine: A Celebration of John Lennon

event.description: Director-choreographer Marcia Milgrom Dodge revives the 1997 Ahrens-Flaherty musicalization of the E.L. Doctorow period classic. Set at the turn of the last century, this wide-canvas tuner follows the hopes and dashed dreams of immigrants and minorities in New York, against a backdrop of doings by historic personalities: Harry Houdini, Emma Goldman and Evelyn Nesbit. Ages 9 and up.

event.identifier: The School of Russian American Ballet presents The Nutcracker
event.description: Earlier this year Mayor Bloomberg named the School of Russian American Ballet one of the best for young audiences. That means its production of the beloved holiday classic is a good bet for kids. Take your tot to marvel at a cast of 80 Russian method-trained dancers and their impossibly-pretty tutus as they pirouette through a seasonal show with a few New York twists. Dances were added to represent the cultural diversity of the Big Apple, with performances showcasing countries including China, Nigeria and India. The second act happens in the Land of Freedom, instead of the Land of Sweets. All ages.
event.sort_string: Russian American Ballet presents The Nutcracker

event.description: Toddlers who want to get a head start on their literacy skills can attend this workshop where they'll make their very own books with the help of French artist and bookmaker, Nathalie Trovato. Kids will sing and read stories to inspire their own animal-shaped book creations. Ages 4 to 6.

This North Carolina–based dad brings his parent-approved hip-hop beats to the city that never sleeps (except for crucial naptimes). As your tot bops, listen for tunes from his Grammy-nominated album, Easy. All ages.

Celebrate Washington’s birthday at the mansion that served as his headquarters during the Revolutionary War. Families can tour the manor with a docent and see where our country’s first President dined with Cabinet members and future Presidents John Adams, Thomas Jefferson and John Quincy Adams. Young history buffs can help create a b-day card for our first Commander-in-Chief, try on colonial costumes and participate in a scavenger hunt. Ages 5 and up.

Besides being able to browse the wares of 20 emerging designers (think apparel, handbags, jewelry, home décor and more) families can enjoy skincare demonstrations, live DJ and raffles. While parents shop, kids can create a holiday craft, have their face painted, or goof around with Santa. All ages.

Starring Montreal duo Jean Saucier and Patrick Côté, this show is a mix of side-splitting comedy and daredevil stunts are the signature of Circo Comedia. Expect lots of clowing, including kid favorites like juggling, roller skates and unicycles. All ages.

The jolly holiday on Broadway continues every time everyone’s favorite English nanny lands onstage at the New Amsterdam. Equally based on the classic 1964 movie and P.L. Travers’s original, darker novel, the show retains the magic of the film but adds a few twists that will surprise those familiar only with Disney’s version of the story. The book is by Julian Fellowes; theatergoers will find a smart, somber-hued extravaganza crisply staged by Richard Eyre and wittily choreographed by Matthew Bourne. Ages 3 and up.
The art institution’s children’s film series features animated shorts depicting the stories Blueberries for Sal and “The Emperor’s New Clothes.” Ages 4 and up.

event.identifier: The Emporer's New Clothes and The Snow Queen
event.description: This season the Brooklyn-bred puppeteer Nicolas Coppola presents two classic Hans Christian Andersen fairytales about royals gone bad. In The Emporer's New Clothes, a self-obsessed tyrant exposes his undies; The Snow Queen pierces a boy’s heart with an icicle, turning him cold as, well, ice. One ticket buys both shows. Ages 3 and up.
event.sort_string: The Emporer's New Clothes and The Snow Queen

event.description: Celebrate the Year of the Tiger at the “Tigers in the House” exhibition, which showcases crafts, masks, and Chinese hand-made prints, all inspired by the big cat. The artist talk includes a tour, plus a draw-a-tiger workshop where your brood can brush up on their stripe-sketching technique with artist, Xiao-Xue. Ages 6 and up.

We’re hip-deep in winter, and already it’s time to start thinking about summer camp options. The entire family is welcome to meet with 70 representatives from local day and sleepaway camps that cater to children with special needs. The fair will also feature information on education and travel opportunities for kids with disabilities. All ages.

Hear stories that highlight Islamic beliefs and manners at the Foundation’s “mommy & me”–style class. Children are exposed to an academic environment in which they can develop listening and social skills and meet positive role models while their parents exchange child-rearing experiences. Ages 1 month to 8 years.

The weather outside may be frightful, but a chilly jaunt through the winter woods could be just what your tween wants. Have her join the Earth Camp head-counselor for an adventure through the park. Advance registration required. Ages 8 to 13.

The New York Gilbert & Sullivan Players’ production of the comic operetta follows the heir of the Mikado (disguised as a wandering musician), who is determined to marry his love even though he’s been told he’ll be executed for doing so. The preshow program (at 12:45pm) is an elucidating, 45-minute chat with artistic director Albert Bergeret about The Mikado’s music, plot and history. All ages.

text.content: $40-$96, children under 13 get in for half price

event.description: This PG-rated documentary from director Kenny Ortega (of High School Musical fame), chronicles the 2009 buildup to what would have been Michael Jackson’s sold-out London concerts. The film, which received mixed (but enthusiastic) reviews when it hit theatres this past fall, showcases the singing and dancing genius of the king of pop, right up until his death. All ages.

event.identifier: Moon over Manhattan—Celebrate the Lunar New Year
event.description: In addition to the ongoing workshops, where youngsters can make their own fortune cookies and origami figures, this afternoon of fun includes a Lion Dance and Kung Fu demonstration at 1pm, and a rendition of the Peking Opera's Journey to the West at 2pm. Then, at 3pm, listen to a story from Justin Roth, the illustrator of the children's book series, Tales of the Chinese Zodiac. All ages.

text.content: Free with museum admission; $10, children under 16 free.

event.sort_string: Moon over Manhattan—Celebrate the Lunar New Year

event.description: French pastry expert Sylvie Berger instructs tykes on how to create Financier chocolat ou framboise, Chocolate and Raspberry Tea Cakes, while they absorb the equally sweet language. Bon appétit! Ages 5 to 11.

In this Italian-born author's newest, Hey, Rabbit, your little ones will find a bunny magician who can pull virtually anything out of his suitcase. From a birthday cake to a jungle, there is nothing too imaginative for this little guy. The double-threat author/illustrator shares stories and offers lessons in drawing. Ages 3 and up.

Festively decorated for the holidays, Little Italy caps off the season with a multicultural parade blending Italian pageantry and customs from neighboring Chinatown: opera singers and dragon dancers, streaming lights and acrobats. Parade begins on Mulberry St at Canal St. All ages.

Argentinian-born performer, educator and cantorial soloist Karina Zilberman celebrates Shabbat with her puppat pal Coco; little ones can sing and dance, or create arts and crafts. Ages newborn to 5 years.

Set against a backdrop of 1950s NYC gang turmoil, this Romeo and Juliet–inspired blockbuster returns to the Great White Way. The bilingual revival—some of the dialogue and songs are in Spanish—is directed by the original show’s librettist, Arthur Laurents, and it features well-loved standards such as “Tonight,” “America,” “Maria,” “I Feel Pretty” and “Somewhere.” Tony-winning choreography by Jerome Robbins will have your tweens wishing they could dance in the aisles. Ages 10 and up.

Take your budding star to this variety show of drama, music and dance. Each of the production’s acts is not only performed by kids ages seven to 18, but was choreographed, staged and written by them too. The only requirement for joining the cast was a commitment to the rehearsal schedule, so the end result may not be full of seasoned professionals, but it will include tons of enthusiasm. All ages.

event.identifier: Thalia Kids Book Club: Walter Dean Myers
event.description: In Myers’s young-adult novel Riot, the New York City draft riots of 1863 are vividly depicted. Today, tweens can hear the book read aloud by the author (a two-time National Book Award finalist), and then tap into their creativity in a writing project. Myers will also be signing copies of the politically minded tome. Ages 12 and up.

text.content: Advance tickets $18, children under 17 $12; day of show $20, children under 17 $14

event.sort_string: Meet the Author: Walter Dean Myers

event.description: Last ticket sold a half-hour before closing. More than 1 million visitors a year flock to the Central Park Zoo for a visit with the sea lions, polar bears and some 200 other species that inhabit this 6.5-acre corner of Central Park. At the penguin house, watch the creatures waddle on firm ground and swim like pros below the waterline. The outdoor Tisch Children's Zoo houses 27 species that enjoy being petted.
Originally produced in Japan and dubbed into English, this sweet live-action film from 1989 centers on the unusual friendship between a tabby cat and a pug. Ages 2 and up.

event.identifier: Family Overture: The Pirates of Penzance
event.description: Arrrr, mateys! Indulge your brood’s (and your own) love of pirates and tongue-twisting songs while introducing them to a classic work of Gilbert and Sullivan. Before the show (at 12:45pm), artistic director Albert Bergeret will discuss the operetta’s history, story and music to help little ones grasp what they’ll later see onstage. All ages.

text.content: $40-$96, children under 13 get in for half-price

event.sort_string: Family Overture: The Pirates of Penzance

event.description: If the weather outside is too frightful, head inside to the Lefferts Historic House to play some rousing games, old-school style. Kids can hone their Nine Man Morris skills and make their own playing board, as well as prep for the spring’s Game of Graces by sharpening dowels and beribboning hoops. Ages 5 and up.

This animated french flick (with english subtitles, so don’t bring your preschool crew!) follows the young Egyptian Princess Akhesa as she journeys down the Nile to find her exiled mother, Queen Nefertiti. Stick around after the screening for related arts and crafts. Ages 7 and up.

Take advantage of the range of activities offered during this Year of the Tiger-themed day. Tots can take in a story or two, brush up on their Mandarin, watch a lion dance performance, have their fortunes told and take a tour of the exhibit, With a Single Step: Stories in the Making of America. All ages.

text.content: $10 per person; ticket grants 50% off admission to Children's Museu of the Arts for the day

event.description: As part of the Big Red Chair Family Series, the Joffrey Ballet School presents its full-length Nutcracker, choreographed by the school’s associate artistic director, Davis Robertson. Students play all of the roles, including the star, the Sugar Plum Fairy. All ages.

Painter Kellyann Monaghan challenges young urbanities to use their hometown as inspiration for compositions depicting NYC’s skyline at night. Kids will come home with their own paintings, and perhaps a greater appreciation for the beauty of Gotham.

Your kiddies may feel they are defying gravity when they complete wicked leaps on the ice. But these thoughts may also result from the show tunes being blasted through the rink. Children attending on their birthdays receive free admission, hot chocolate and popcorn. All ages.

text.content: $5, seniors and children under 15 $3; $6.50 skate rental

event.description: Pig Brooch Theatre Company, cultivated in NYC in 2004, pays homage to the holiday favorite by performing verbatim the television special “A Charlie Brown Christmas.” The show is accompanied by a jazz trio belting out all of the Vince Guaraldi favorites, while the actors have been trained to match the exact voices and physicality of the cartoon characters. This play is a gentle reminder of what the holidays signify as the Peanuts crew shows Charlie Brown what Christmas is all about. All ages.

This annual street fair abounds with interactive booths manned by neighborhood galleries and businesses, performances by local music and dance groups, and food from some of Chelsea’s culinary stars, including milk shake king Ronnybrook Farm Dairy. Your kids should be pleased to get a taste—literally—of what the Chelsea area has to offer. All ages.

In a program for families that honors African-American culture and history, kids can design and stamp African-style mud cloth (a fabric painted with river soil) and, on Sunday only, hear Kwanzaa-themed stories. Ages 5 to 10.

event.identifier: Purim Carnival at the 92nd Street Y
event.description: Besides parading around in masks and costumes, playing games and noshing on Purim treats, kids can also hear the story of Purim and meet the heroes of the Megillah: Queen Esther and King Ahashverosh. Prizes will be awarded to the best-costumed kids. All ages.
event.sort_string: Purim Carnival at the 92nd Street Y

event.description: Brooklynites might want to make this hour-long story session part of their regular weekend routine. Every Sunday afternoon, Yuval Gans, a father and the owner of the store, reads classics like Madeline and Dr. Seuss in addition to newer selections, and he accompanies the tales with acoustic guitar. The storytimes are informal and free of charge, but parents are encouraged to call in advance and alert the staff to the size of their party. Ages 1 to 5.

Regardless of your little one’s ice-skating skills, she’s bound to have a good time gliding on the ice while listening to hits by the Fab Four. Children attending on their birthdays are treated to free admission, hot chocolate and popcorn. All ages.

text.content: $5, seniors and children under 15 $3, skate rental $6.50

event.description: The BPC is one of our favorite below-the-radar venues, not least because the casual space has retained that artsy old East Village vibe. This year-end dance party gets started a few days early with noisy horns, balloons and hats, confetti and kid-friendly tunes by the Ben Rudnick and Friends band. All ages.

You’ll get a kick (get it?) out of this holiday stalwart, which—after 77 years—still features Santa, wooden soldiers and the Rockettes, albeit with updated, kickier (we could go on all day) choreography. All ages.
Children's author and poet Richard Lewis hosts an interactive an afternoon of interactive activities for kids. The Touchstone Theatre Ensemble adds in a healthy dose of theater and music. All ages.

text.content: $10 per child/adult pair; $5 for each additional child; $10 per adult without child

event.description: THIS EVENT IS STILL BEING CONFIRMED. A favorite of kids and parents alike, Peter of the Grammy-winning ’60s trio Peter, Paul and Mary performs numbers from his book-and-CD sets, The Peter Yarrow Songbook: Favorite Folk Songs and The Peter Yarrow Songbook: Sleepytime Songs. Ages 3 and up.

In this hour-long Sesame flick, the ticklish red Muppet broadens his knowledge of winter holidays (Christmas, Hanukkah and Kwanzaa) on his quest to find a gift for his goldfish, Dorothy. Don’t flee during the credits: The screening is followed by a holiday raffle. Ages 2 to 6.
By traveling through a human-size anthill and transporting larvae, kids get practice at being bugs (we’re not sure when that will come in handy though).

Within the gates of this institution—home to more than 4,500 creatures—young visitors can come nose to nose (or snout, or beak) with animal ambassadors from all across the globe. At the Monkey House, newly reopened after a three-month renovation, kids can check out the squirrel monkeys and pygmy marmosets, and watch zookeepers give etiquette lessons to primates. Jungle World, an indoor replication of an Asian tropical rain forest, houses cute critters such as baby langurs and small-claw otters. Another ideal cool-weather exhibit is the one-acre Himalayan Highlands, where foundling snow leopard Leo has a temporary residence.

Just in time for Black History Month, dive into the richness of African sounds and rhythms with the energetic moves of award-winning dance company, Forces of Nature. Jazz, modern dance, swing, R&B, hip hop—it’s all covered here and sure to get you and yours grooving. All ages.

event.identifier: El Encuentro de Juan Bobo y Pedro Animal/The Encounter
event.description: When the two frazzled, somewhat clueless puppets in this comical production face a problem, the audience is encouraged to shout out the solution (think of it as a less-annoying version of grown-ups yelling at the movie screen). The pair of slapstick characters—one Dominican, one Puerto Rican—are presented in a sensory-enveloping bilingual environment complete with live music, dancing and world-class puppetry. Ages 5 and up.
event.sort_string: El Encuentro de Juan Bobo y Pedro Animal/The Encounter

event.description: Using costumes, photographs and props, this exhibit explores the essential link between New York and the theater. Highlights include a version of Mrs. Potts’s costume from the original Broadway production of Disney’s Beauty and the Beast, a spectacular confection in silk, pearls, beads and lace that was, at first, too big to fit through the backstage door.

The venerable modern dance troupe performs pieces spanning its 20-year evolution. Two separate programs have been slated for the run, and usually only program A is kid-appropriate. These matinees of Program B, however, have been adapted for little audiences. Watch for 1981’s Caught, in which a dancer flies above the stage, leaping over 100 times in less than six minutes. Home to the largest and arguably most fabulous collection of dinosaur fossils in the world, AMNH’s fourth-floor dino halls have been blowing people’s minds for decades. Roughly 80% of the bones on display were actually dug out of the ground by Indiana Jones types. The thrills begin when you cross the threshold of the Theodore Roosevelt Rotunda, where you’re confronted with a towering barosaurus that’s rearing high on its hind legs to protect its young from an attacking allosaurus – an impressive welcome to the world’s largest museum of its kind. During the museum’s mid 1990s renovation, several specimens were remodelled to incorporate discoveries made during that time. The Tyrannosaurus rex, for instance, was once believed to have walked upright, Godzilla-style; it now stalks prey with its head lowered and tail raised parallel to the ground. The rest of the museum is equally dramatic. The newly opened Hall of Human Origins boasts a fine display of your old cousins, the Neanderthals. The Hall of Biodiversity examines world ecosystems and environmental preservation, and a life-size model of a blue whale hangs from the cavernous ceiling of the Hall of Ocean Life. The impressive Hall of Meteorites was brushed up and reorganised in 2003. The space’s focal point is Ahnighito, the largest iron meteor on display anywhere in the world, weighing in at 34 tons (more than 30,000kg). The spectacular $210 million Rose Center for Earth & Space – dazzling to come upon at night – is a giant silvery globe where you can discover the universe via 3-D shows in the Hayden Planetarium and light shows in the Big Bang Theater. An IMAX theatre screens larger-than-life nature programmes, and you can always learn something new from the innovative temporary exhibitions, an easily accessible research library (with vast photo and print archives), several cool gift shops and friendly, helpful staff.

text.content: Brooklyn’s premier institution is a tranquil alternative to Manhattan’s big-name spaces. Among the museum’s assets is a rich, 4,000-piece Egyptian collection, which includes a gilded-ebony statue of Amenhotep III and, on a ceiling, a large-scale rendering of an ancient map of the cosmos. You can even view a mummy preserved in its original coffin. The two-storey, skylit Beaux-Arts Court, where they’re usually displayed, is undergoing restoration, including a new structural glass floor that will enhance the light-suffused centrepiece of the landmark building. On the fifth floor, American paintings and sculptures include native son Thomas Cole’s The Pic-Nic and Louis Rémy Mignot’s Niagara. Don’t miss the renowned Pacific Island and African galleries (this was the first American museum to display African objects as art). In spring 2007 the museum opened the Elizabeth Sackler Center for Feminist Art; at its core is Judy Chicago’s monumental 1979 sculpture The Dinner Party, arguably the movement’s most famous work.

text.content: The delay-addled construction on ‘St John the Unfinished’ began in 1892 in Romanesque style, was put on hold for a Gothic Revival redesign in 1911, then ground to a halt in 1941, when the US entered World War II. It resumed in earnest in 1979, but a fire in 2001 destroyed the church’s gift shop and damaged two 17th-century Italian tapestries, which has delayed completion further. In addition to Sunday services, the cathedral hosts concerts and tours. It bills itself as a place for all people—and it means it. Annual events include both winter and summer solstice celebrations; the Blessing of the Animals during the Feast of St Francis, which draws pets and their people from all over the city; and, would you believe it, the Blessing of the Bikes, which kicks off the bicycle season each spring.

text.content: The neoclassical New York City Ballet headlines at this opulent theater, which Philip Johnson designed to resemble a jewel box. NYCB has two seasons: Winter begins just before Thanksgiving and features more than a month of performances of George Balanchine’s magical The Nutcracker; the repertory season continues through February. The eight-week spring season usually begins in April. The best seats are in the first ring, where the music comes through loud and clear, but—even better—one can enjoy the dancers’ patterns from anywhere in the theater. Choreography is by Balanchine (the 89-by-58-foot stage was made to his specifications); Jerome Robbins; Peter Martins, the company’s ballet master in chief; and Christopher Wheeldon, the resident choreographer, whose innovative work has injected the troupe with new life.

Occupying 13 acres of Central Park, the Metropolitan Museum of Art, which opened in 1880, is impressive in terms both of quality and scale. Added in 1895 by McKim, Mead and White, the neoclassical facade is daunting. However, the museum is surprisingly easy to negotiate, particularly if you come early on a weekday and avoid the crowds. In the ground floor’s north wing sits the collection of Egyptian art and the glass-walled atrium housing the Temple of Dendur, moved en masse from its original Nile-side setting and now overlooking a reflective pool. Antiquity is also well represented in the southern wing of the ground floor by the halls housing Greek and Roman art, which reopened in 2007 after receiving an elegant makeover. Turning west brings you to the Arts of Africa, Oceania and the Americas collection; it was donated by Nelson Rockefeller as a memorial to his son Michael, who disappeared while visiting New Guinea in 1961. A wider-ranging bequest, the two-story Robert Lehman Wing, can be found at the western end of the floor. This eclectic collection is housed in a re-creation of his townhouse and features Bellini’s masterful Madonna and Child. Rounding out the ground-floor highlights is the American Wing on the northwest corner. Its Engelhard Court reopened in spring 2009 as part of the wing’s current revamp. Now more a sculpture court than an interior garden, it houses large-scale 19th-century works in bronze and marble—and one of its three fountains is by Tiffany.

Established in 1887, the Eldridge Street Synagogue was among the earliest temples founded in America by the new wave of Eastern European Jews. MoMA contains the world’s finest and most comprehensive holdings of 20th-century art, and, thanks to a sweeping redesign by architect Yoshio Taniguchi, completed in 2004, it is now able to show off much more of its immense permanent collection in serene, high-ceilinged galleries that almost outshine the art on display. Highlights like Van Gogh’s The Starry Night may be what keeps the tourists flocking to the Museum of Modern Art, but even the most jaded New Yorkers swoon when they enter the spacious galleries and the soaring five-storey atrium, the central artery for the six curatorial departments: Architecture and Design, Drawings, Painting and Sculpture, Photography, Prints and Illustrated Books, and Film and Media. Works include the best creations from the hands of Matisse, Picasso, Van Gogh, Giacometti, Lawrence, Pollock, Rothko and Warhol, among many others. Outside, Philip Johnson’s sculpture garden has been restored to its original, larger plan from 1953, and its powerful minimalist sculptures and sheer matte black granite and glass wall are overlooked by the Modern, the sleek high-end restaurant and bar run by Midas-touch restaurateur Danny Meyer; for a more affordable, but no less impressive, dining experience, try the Bar Room at the Modern. The museum’s eclectic exhibition of design objects is a must-see, with examples of art nouveau, the Bauhaus and Vienna Secession alongside a vintage 1946 Ferrari and architectural drawings from the likes of Rem Koolhaas and Mies van der Rohe.

Located at the northern end of Museum Mile, this institution contains a wealth of city history and includes paintings, sculptures, photographs, military and naval uniforms, theater memorabilia, manuscripts, ship models and rare books. The extensive toy collection, full of New Yorkers’ playthings dating from the colonial era to the present, is especially well loved. Toy trains, lead soldiers and battered teddy bears share shelf space with exquisite bisque dolls (decked out in extravagant Paris fashions) and lavishly appointed dolls’ houses. Don’t miss the amazing Stettheimer Dollhouse, created during the 1920s by Carrie Stettheimer, whose artist friends re-created their masterpieces in miniature to hang on the walls. Look closely and you’ll even spy a tiny version of Marcel Duchamp’s famous Nude Descending a Staircase. Don’t miss the museum’s Timescapes, a 25-minute multimedia film that tells NYC’s glorious story from 1624 to the present. The film is free with admission and plays throughout the day.

New York's “biggest little zoo” is an eight-acre haven for southern and eastern African leopards, mandrills, lizards, antelope and lemurs. Face snakes head-on in the “Fear Zone,” part of the zoo's newly renovated Reptile Wing, which opened in 2007. At the children's center, kids can feed domesticated animals such as donkeys, goats, pigs and deer.

Boasting 18 miles of books, the Strand has a mammoth collection of more than 2 million discount volumes, and the store is made all the more daunting by its chaotic, towering shelves and surly staff. Reviewer discounts are in the basement, while rare volumes lurk upstairs. If you spend enough time here you can find just about anything, from that out-of-print Victorian book on manners to the kitschiest of sci-fi pulp.

The World Music Institute presents many international dance troupes here, but there are also seasons at the more intimate Thalia, featuring contemporary choreographers such as Brian Brooks and Larry Keigwin.

The Jewish Museum, housed in the 1908 Warburg Mansion, contains a fascinating collection of more than 28,000 works of art, artifacts and media installations. The two-floor permanent exhibition, “Culture and Continuity: The Jewish Journey,” examines how Judaism has survived and explores various Jewish identities throughout history. The Café Weissman serves contemporary kosher fare.

This Madison Avenue institution began as the private library of savvy financier J. Pierpont Morgan, and is his artistic gift to the city. Building on the collection Morgan amassed in his lifetime, the museum houses first-rate works on paper, including drawings by Michelangelo, Rembrandt and Picasso; three Gutenberg Bibles; a copy of Frankenstein annotated by Mary Shelley; manuscripts by Dickens, Poe, Twain, Steinbeck and Wilde; sheet music handwritten by Beethoven and Mozart; and an original edition of Dickens’ A Christmas Carol that’s displayed every yuletide. In 2006, a massive renovation and expansion orchestrated by Renzo Piano brought more natural light into the building and doubled the available exhibition space.

The only institution of its kind in the world, this modest space explores high-rise buildings as objects of design, products of technology, real-estate investments, and places of work and residence. Recent exhibits have covered architectural fantasies of the early 20th century, and charted the progress of the new World Trade Center complex and Burj Dubai—the massive cloud-buster in the United Arab Emirates that will be the world’s tallest building when it’s completed in late 2009.

This fascinating museum—actually a series of restored tenement apartments at 97 Orchard St—is accessible only by guided tour. Tickets are purchased at the visitors’ center at 108 Orchard St; tours often sell out, so it’s wise to book ahead. Costumed interpreters recount the daily lives of individual immigrant clans that called the building home over the decades. “Getting By” visits the Sicilian Baldizzi family residence in apartment No. 5 in the 1930s, while “Piecing It Together” pays a call on the Russian Rogarshevsky family, mourning the loss of patriarch Abraham, a garment worker who died of tuberculosis in 1918. “The Moores: An Irish Family in America,” revisits a Dublin family who lived in the building in 1869.

text.content: Like the Guggenheim, the Whitney is set apart by its unique architecture: it’s a Marcel Breuer-designed grey granite cube with an all-seeing upper-storey ‘eye’ window. When Gertrude Vanderbilt Whitney, a sculptor and art patron, opened the museum in 1931, she dedicated it to living American artists. Today, the Whitney holds about 15,000 pieces by nearly 2,000 artists, including Alexander Calder, Willem de Kooning, Edward Hopper (the museum holds his entire estate), Jasper Johns, Louise Nevelson, Georgia O’Keeffe and Claes Oldenburg. Still, the museum’s reputation rests mainly on its temporary shows, particularly the exhibition everyone loves to hate, the Whitney Biennial. Held in even-numbered years, the Biennial remains the most prestigious (and controversial) assessment of contemporary art in America. The Whitney’s small midtown Altria branch, located in a corporate atrium space across the street from Grand Central Terminal, mounts solo commissioned projects. At the main building, there are free guided tours daily and live performances on select Friday nights. Sarabeth’s, the museum’s café, is open daily till 4.30pm, offering sandwiches and the like. In 2007, the Whitney confirmed plans to open a separate museum outpost in the new High Line park.

Geeks, rejoice: The tech magazine’s pop-up boutique returns to Soho for its third year. Gadget lovers can test more than 100 cutting-edge products, including messenger bags outfitted with solar panels to recharge your cell phone ($170), climate-controlled strollers ($2,500) and, of course, the world’s first $250 million female robot, before logging on to the website to make your purchases. Surprisingly, the temporary joint also offers lo-fi delights such as Wednesday-night DJ sessions and holiday scavenger hunts on Sunday afternoons.
